commit_message:
Centralize exception management for Neutron

A common pattern we use is to catch OpenStack clients exceptions and
re-raise an OpenStackCloud* exceptions.
Moreover, we need to distinguish NeutronClientException with status
code 404 from other Neutron exceptions in order to handle Rax broken
catalog (i.e. falling-through and using Nova API).

This patch centralises all that.

Change-Id: Ia14083bee7988e90a9e5ce04305a8ead4511b3d3

[{'created': '2015-06-19 08:16:26.000000000', 'message': "Pin keystonemiddleware max version

To resolve requirements conflicts in most painless way before 6.1 GA
let's ping keystonemiddleware to max version 2.0.0 and in 7.0 we

Change-Id: I98055060480a2ef80b9d56a211812e98e27fa2e1
Closes-Bug: #1466733
"}]
commit_message:
Pin keystonemiddleware max version

To resolve requirements conflicts in most painless way before 6.1 GA
let's ping keystonemiddleware to max version 2.0.0 and in 7.0 we
can remove upper bounds as well update packages in our mirros.

Change-Id: I98055060480a2ef80b9d56a211812e98e27fa2e1
Closes-Bug: #1466733

commit_message:
Create keystone user in start.sh if it doesn't exist

This is required for the source install method (for packages the
user/group is added as part of install)

patch looks good, but agree common would be a superior name for the directory so changing vote to -1 to indicate work needs to be done on this patch.  otherwise the concept is good for +2 :)'}, {'account_id': 13039, 'date': '2015-06-14 08:46:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Definitely rename docker/base/ to docker/common/.

I'd rather move kolla-common.sh and service_hosts.sh to a new docker/common/base/ directory as well.

Also all {centos,fedora}-{binary,rdo}-base should be merged with only a 'base' directory left. I think the easiest is probably to rebase on Id63eac1eb9893ceb775c28bf22842dede85c214a -- which has a conflict at the moment, I'm going to push a new version in a sec.

Looks good otherwise.

How do you plan to handle differences in start scripts after we add support for more distros? I'm thinking about packages install (packages might have different names), and other disto-specific steps.

@sdake: what's the process to have this patch merged? shouldn't we approve the blueprint first?"}, {'account_id': 13039, 'date': '2015-06-14 11:54:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Paul, forget my comment about packages install, I forgot the dockerfiles are still in distro specific folders :)'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-06-14 16:28:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@mandre,

Each project has latitude to define their own blueprint process.

What I do is new blueprints go into the "Discussion" state where discussion happens about them in the whiteboard, irc, or team meetings.  If the discussion meets a conclusion (which it looks like this one does with bmace's comments) then someone from the core team can approve the blueprint, assign it a priority, and assign it to a milestone (such as l1, l2, l3). revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-10 11:07:04.000000000', 'message': 'Symlink all non Dockerfile resources in images

The only files in the docker image directories that differ majorly
between distros are the Dockerfiles (e.g. different package manager
mechanisms, different repo sources, etc).

The supporting files such as the start.sh/check.sh and config files
should largely stay the same between base images.

This change moves these files up into a "base" directory, and symlinks
them in the same way that the build script is managed. This means when
adding a new base distro only new Dockerfiles need to be created. Also,
if a distro does happen to require a vastly different start.sh script
for example, one can choose to simply not symlink to the base and
instead drop in a custom one.

Implements: blueprint refactor-base-image-layout

Change-Id: Ic4db69d31ff54a1fb95af4853a2e5ae490064284

commit_message:
Symlink all non Dockerfile resources in images

The only files in the docker image directories that differ majorly between
distros are the Dockerfiles (e.g. different package manager mechanisms,
different repo sources, etc).

The supporting files such as the start.sh/check.sh and config files should
largely stay the same between base images.

This change moves these files up into a "common" directory, and symlinks them
in the same way that the build script is managed. This means when adding a new
base distro only new Dockerfiles need to be created. Also, if a distro does
happen to require a vastly different start.sh script for example, one can
choose to simply not symlink to the common and instead drop in a custom one.

Implements: blueprint refactor-base-image-layout

Change-Id: Ic4db69d31ff54a1fb95af4853a2e5ae490064284

commit_message:
[Heat] Add rally template with Heat Resource Group

The patch adds a rally template for
Heat.create_and_delete_stack scenario that allows
to test performance of creation and deletion of Heat
Resource Groups.
The template allows to create a stack that contain
N instances and N volumes attached, where N - is
num_instances parameter in rally template.

Change-Id: If5c7c787c670b464eb3386635bcb1bfc5a218075

commit_message:
Neutron l3, dhcp, ovs, metadata agents now are independed.

Removing co-location between agents prevent us from unrequired
start/stop operations for agents.

Since Juno agents dependency no more need, end even harmful.

Change-Id: I35358dae14ae73e720b705c2d7a46825a1be8fca
Closes-bug: #1459528

commit_message:
Generate consistent length passwords in AIO

The bootstrap-aio.sh script generates a password by reading a set number
of characters from urandom then removing those that aren't alphanumeric.
The problem with this is that its possible for 0 characters to remain.

This patch changes the order so that tr (translate) reads urandom
directly and removes non alphanumeric characters then that output is
truncated to the required length. This ensures the generated password is
always the desired length.

Change-Id: I03984ab891f88fe4b064f7f7fcb71edf48096493
Closes-Bug: #1465684

Bascially in favor of this with some caveats.

The only thing that should be in an unscoped token catalog is the Keystone (idenityt) entry iteslef.


That said, Nova should not be using an unscoped token with Keystone.  If it needs to create a user, that create should be scoped to a domain.  While I do think you want the tokenless auth (X509) support, it should still be considered a scoped call.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-12 18:43:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-06-12 21:18:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-12 21:23:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-keystone-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/32/190732/4/check/gate-keystone-specs-docs/2b5050d//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 3m 10s
- gate-keystone-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/32/190732/4/check/gate-keystone-specs-python27/148a95b/ : SUCCESS in 1m 59s'}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2015-06-17 20:59:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(4 comments)

In principle I like this idea'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-06-17 21:25:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

So...I think this is a dupe:  Jamie Lennox had been working on a comparable spec already, but it only had the Keystone server in it.

I don't want people thinking they can use the Unscoped tokens outside of Keystone, and a generic Service Catalog in an unscoped token will do that.   It is the wrong tool for what you are trying to do.  Even if all you are about its identity, you should use a scoped token.  If you need some other form of scoping then propose that."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-06-17 23:38:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Have a link to that spec?

There are services that expect a keystone token, but don't need scoping to any project to work since they use acl's for permissions. Why is using an unscoped token for this use case bad? Why is making a dummy project, then scoping the user to that dummy project any better?"}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-06-18 18:31:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

I agree with the others. May want to explore other alternatives like X.509 cert auth as the instances does not need an interactive account.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-06-18 18:55:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-06-19 15:43:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I can't find the spec, but the meaning for it is very different than this spec.  Jamie was doing it so that multiple auth URLS could have different protection mechanisms,  Federation is pretty much replacing that need now, so he may well have abandonded it.


The -2 still stands:  we should not be using unscoped tokens outside of Keystone.  The service catalog associated with the token is scoped to the project, and the the service catalog is how we find the services.  Putting those into unscoped tokens will not match the concept that the catalog is coped;  we would  need to start scoping the catalog to the user, not the resource.  Users are not provided carte blache aspect to services in OpenStack, but should be limited to those associated with their projects.

In short, an operation against anything but Keystone should not use an unscoped token."}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-06-19 16:15:51.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fix function name reference in cinder.service.spec.js

This patch fixes a typo when referencing tested function names
in the it block that iterates over the tests array, so the
correct names are displayed in Jasmine spec runner.

Change-Id: I2685272063b1a599d0c4356e234a779c63d099e1
Closes-Bug: #1466543

That will keep everything in one branch and submit a new patch on the first set.

I also don't think you need to declare it is your first change. :)

Without declaring a dependency, secret.xml can be

Closes-bug: #1458628
Change-Id: I0b9aec13866e4e334bcaf967192b2bc310ae20fb

commit_message:
Ensure /etc/nova exists before creating secret.xml

Without declaring a dependency, secret.xml can be
created before the folder is created through
the installation of the nova packages.

Closes-bug: #1458628
Change-Id: I0b9aec13866e4e334bcaf967192b2bc310ae20fb

commit_message:
NexentaStor SA: get the right LUN from mapping

In case there are several mappings for a ZVol hardcoded '0'
will result in failure of volume attachement by Nova.

Change-Id: I3f0e1ce86864eb3c496da02e4c4bdb635bbeb799
Closes-Bug: 1430961

Add designate-sink service

Container for Designate Sink, automatic domain creation for
enabled notification handlers (nova and/or neutron).

Change-Id: I41118cb149e7f39a17bff49123d82905b51b7939
Blueprint: designate-container

commit_message:
Cleanup session creation

When using the session object we want to pass through unknown kwargs to
the adapter so that keystoneclient can add new parameters as required.

This requires fixing the old options so that we can restrict what is
passed and showing a warning when there are values that are being
ignored.

Change-Id: Ia795dfc8e16c60a08df1636816daefe2ebbd0b03

commit_message:
Introduce Guru Meditation Reports into Cinder

This commit integrates functionality from the
`openstack.common.report` module into Cinder.
This enables Cinder services to receive SIGUSR1
and print a Guru Meditation Report to stderr.
The required modules were added to
'openstack-common.conf' as well.

It is essentially a copy from implementation of
nova side.

Change-Id: I5bbdc0f97db9b0ebd7b48e50ab7869e2ca33aead
Implements: blueprint guru-meditation-report

Add initial "Open Source" chapter

First verison of the "Open Source" chapter covering:
- Open Source At The Core
- Acceptable Licensing
- Dependencies and Optional Modules

commit_message:
Add initial "Release management" chapter

First bits of the new "Release management" chapter, covering:
- Common time-based release model
- Independent release model

TODO: Library release model, Feature branches...

commit_message:
Update of `support-modify-volume-image-metadata.rst`

Since snapshot is immutable, we shouldn't provide the capability
to update image metadata referenced with snapshot.
And part of this Spec is not well formatted, we should update it
to make it easier to read after the rst file is coverted into html
file, overall changes is listed below.

- Remove snapshot relevant changes in the SPEC.
- Fix the incorrect format which will cause the html version
  hard to read.
- Update the work items to reflect the latest changes.

Change-Id: I935ae67bca17c2eaa673d87403c0cfa8068f0922

commit_message:
Permits created guests to reach external networks

Adds MASQUERADE target on FLAT_INTERFACE in order to permit the
created guests to reach external networks.   This patch is needed
in order to avoid manual operations when testing guests connectivity.
In your local.conf file, add ALLOW_EGRESS=True in order to enable it.

Change-Id: If60d76497b19da3d936a599e142720ddcee8284b
Closes-bug: #1461228

commit_message:
fix typo for server create in server.rst

we have <security-group-list> in server create option,
while <security-group-name> in the explanation, they
both should be <security-group-name>.

Closes-Bug: #1466742
Change-Id: I26a25f57e57d8f9e19ec9c9ccb3c2b8d5396b78d

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
fix DHCP port changed when dhcp-agent restart

When DHCP server is started, the periodic task is running
before loading cache state.The method port_update_end
need to use the cache information, but the cache information
has not been loaded.

Change-Id: I0d1da11bb559b7f0f9d4428b82573fb26916a933
Closes-Bug: #1420042

For deployments running db engines that enforce strict FK matching, they have not been able to create a db yet, so this patch fixes it for them. Now they can create the db and the key is the right size.

For deployments with non-strict engines that have already created this wrong-sized FK, we need a migration from current head in the vpnaas migration branch that conditionally adjusts the size:

  if sizeof(ipsec_site_conn_id) != 36:
    adjust size of ipsec_site_conn_id field, preserving data

That should fix it for existing deployments with the wrong size while skipping the adjustment if not needed. (This conditional migration should go in the neutron-vpnaas repo.)

At least that's what I think we could do. Ann should check my logic."}, {'account_id': 13671, 'date': '2015-06-10 16:07:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Fix cisco_csr_identifier_map.ipsec_site_conn_id

Some database engines require exact match of sizes of foreign keys
and referenced fields. Foreign key ipsec_site_conn_id of table
cisco_csr_identifier_map is varchar(64) but it references field
id varchar(36) of table ipsec_site_connections. This gives error
while running migration scripts in such databases.

This fix only applies to new installations. Existing databases will
be corrected by migration scripts introduced in
https://review.openstack.org/190569 - they will take care of resizing
the field and adjusting the model.

Change-Id: I6cc9625a2d96d1330b06eb727cc7fa5363c697b8
Depends-On: I384a9bbaba05ef94174b666bdcfb276eedc74134
Closes-Bug: #1463806

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

(1 comment)

We have no need to change requirements, we aren't requiring any additional functionality/bug fix from the library from Cinder. We are just making sure to use the most up to date namespace for the library in the system/venv. 

Last time we updated requirements for rtslib-fb was because we needed the saving configuration functionality that was added in 2.1.41, and that made sense.

But to change the requirements to remove 1 try...except seems a little over the top to me.

That's my point of view, but I have no problem bumping the version and removing the try...except if that's what you guys think is best."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-06-16 15:08:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

[{'created': '2015-06-10 10:07:37.000000000', 'message': 'Use correct rtslib namespace for newer versions

For rtslib-fb versions 2.1.52 and newer its own namespace (rtslib_fb) is
recommended instead of the older one (rtslib).

On versions with this new namespace a deprecation warning will be
thrown: "'rtslib' package name for rtslib-fb is deprecated, please
instead import 'rtslib_fb'"

commit_message:
Use correct rtslib namespace for newer versions

For rtslib-fb versions 2.1.52 and newer its own namespace (rtslib_fb) is
recommended instead of the older one (rtslib).

On versions with this new namespace a deprecation warning will be
thrown: "'rtslib' package name for rtslib-fb is deprecated, please
instead import 'rtslib_fb'"

This patch uses this new namespace when possible and falls back to the
older namespace if not.

Change-Id: I984105458da4d7b8736bf7c83919cbe5feb9c85a
Closes-Bug: #1460814

commit_message:
Fix noVNC console access for an IPv6 setup

Following a recent change in websocket proxy code
(commit: fdb73a2d445971c6158a80692c6f74094fd4193a),
novnc console access is not working for IPv6 addresses.
This patch fixes the issue by taking into account the way
IPv6 urls are constructed and parsing them accordingly.

Closes-Bug: #1456963
Change-Id: Ia6c50be1e3cbe8a21f0a75b6a7cebd1712d311f8

commit_message:
Catch all exceptions around port for ip finding

If neutron does not work, then it's going to throw inside of list_ports,
which is going to send an OpenStackCloudException through search_ports,
which is then not going to be caught by the NeutronClientException trap
here.

Change-Id: Id25ff2688de55f4b39a145185269bc7b7ccb89eb

commit_message:
Refactor node's and driver's vendor passthru to a common place

This patch is refactoring the node's and driver's vendor passthru in the
API to a common place (utils.py). Historically this code was duplicated
because each endpoint supported different things (driver's vendor
passhtru endpoing being always synchrounous and node's being always
asyncronous), since now both endpoints supports the same features and
the code is almost the same it makes sense to have it in a common place,
so changing once will affect both.

Related-Blueprint: ipxe-dynamic-config
Change-Id: I16be0c787993240e55ceb13b29bcb18c21151722

subject: Change return value of [driver_]vendor_passthru to dict

commit_message:
Change return value of [driver_]vendor_passthru to dict

This is a refactor patch that changes the return value of the
vendor_passthru() and driver_vendor_passthru() RPC methods to a dictionary
instead of a tuple. By doing that we make it easy to extend for future
improvements.

The RPC version was bumped to 1.29 by this change.

Change-Id: I8729bb85d97a563d4ec8409ecd0eba15dc0c51bc
Related-Blueprint: ipxe-dynamic-config

commit_message:
Adding unit test coverage for the validate method

Adding a case in the existing unit tests to cover the ValueError
exception in the validate method of the GetInput classs. Also adding
a new yaml.

Change-Id: Ib5436d2e54cf03ea1abd03e4da3bfc7c6cc12959
Closes-Bug: #1466657

commit_message:
JSCS cleanup - horizon/static/framework conf and util

We need to do cleanup before we can enable JSCS globally
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185725/).

This patch excludes the 'util/tech-debt' folder which is
covered in patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188316/.

Change-Id: I0b3e6435d48a24c0b24e38c96b1ce679c3268300
Partially-Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup

commit_message:
Cinder container

Cinder is going to be split up into four containers.
- cinder-api
- cinder-scheduler
- cinder-volume
- cinder-backup

Co-Authored-By: Daneyon Hansen <danehans@cisco.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ian Main <imain@redhat.com>

Implements: blueprint cinder-container
Closes-bug: #1460136

Change-Id: I688471151ffa54d547b9aa0f2f2e2ea7f68f288d

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

(15 comments)

Galera is nice in terms of HA mysql, so good work :)

In general, other projects are moving straight to galera even for simple non-HA single node setups. I'd rather see we do that as well when it comes to mysql so every setup is prepared for HA (and is using the same type of backend), instead of adding in a 2nd mysql-ish container.

commit_message:
Galera container

This changes are providing support for galera cluster. It's important for
project to has got support for database cluster as a one of the steps to
providing High Avability(HA) in Kolla project

Change-Id: If51bb88ab05972d3b8aa8abbbbd2a5480213a10e
Implemented: blueprint galera-container

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Change-Id: Ida50fc2a187f08e0da53f27ae88e9ccce4f6b862

commit_message:
zuul: actually enable puppet4 voting

In a previous patch, I attempted to make puppet4 jobs voting for Puppet
OpenStack modules, after Juno release.
This patch aims to actually enable the voting.

Change-Id: I77cc8b6f3c0cd3ace7485ce67c81b3a7476427fe

commit_message:
Fix beaker on Trusty and  update .gitreview file

* Update .gitreview file because of Puppet OpenStack modules project
  renaming.
* Fix Beaker tests on Ubuntu Trusty (newline added if secret)

We have to do that in a single patch because:
* project has been renamed so gitreview needs to be updated
* beaker jobs are voting

Co-Authored-By: Jeremy Stanley <fungi@yuggoth.org>
Co-Authored-By: Emilien Macchi <emilien@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sebastien Badia <sbadia@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1465780
Change-Id: If562aa5bc969c316fd8fd0cb06ed7115c465a57d

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

commit_message:
Add lbaas configuration opt in config-reference

neutron-lbaas has now its own repository and the configuration options have
moved in different files. This should be reflected in the admin-cloud-guide
and the configuration reference.

Change-Id: Id3c3e0c85b214114d5c98000bc5d7916c5d65b49
Closes-Bug: #1449847

commit_message:
Add client_socket_timeout option

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour.  Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 9292
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: 1371022
Change-Id: I9e7edcbf25ece61dc16b8cd5a8bef5ed9a14e3d6

commit_message:
Change set_override() calls to use flags() instead

A few test cases used the set_override() method to change
the CONF variables instead of self.flags().  This goes against
the nova hacking rules since it can affect down stream test
cases.

Change-Id: Iff2b38cda5cd773887f36f765013fe4adfada35b

commit_message:
Add Link to governance.openstack.org to docs.o.o pages

commit_message:
Add glance_store to projects.txt

glance requires glance_store but the requirements in glance_store on
master and stable/kilo don't line up with what's in
global-requirements.txt so add glance_store to projects.txt to sync
those up.

Conflicts:
        projects.txt

Closes-Bug: #1454695
Related-Bug: #1454467

Change-Id: Ib41b0c482edf39017f26e483cd3661ca5b540133
(cherry picked from commit 64091866112ac6b3590de8b6d3c036cc03dcd6e0)

commit_message:
Fixed issue with rabbitmq_ha_queues for Heat

We can see on HA deployments 'rabbitmq_ha_queues=False' in Heat
configuration file. In the result Heat doesn't work after the
destructive scenarios.

Change-Id: Iaa77b875928b94b79ab8a5e039cbbfe0d1908b35
Closes-Bug: #1465840

commit_message:
Revert "added a 'shared' column in FW policy table"

This reverts commit 00ec2e418e7b8b645bd4f9993433f58aac7f6074.

The same change went in with commit 92b9e4071a359b4516c1530af9cb74b7d5fa35e3
a few hours earlier. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190023/4

This commit is completely redundant and unnecessary.

Change-Id: I4ba318676a07e5b79fb011144f2ba21422a79457

commit_message:
Fixed issue with rabbitmq_ha_queues for Heat

We can see on HA deployments 'rabbitmq_ha_queues=False' in Heat
configuration file. In the result Heat doesn't work after the
destructive scenarios.

Change-Id: I7b800e7414fa40f1b23690de6e03d36bd62fe161
Closes-Bug: #1466810

reach consensus.

More details at: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/StableBranch'}, {'account_id': 10795, 'date': '2015-04-03 07:22:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi,

Earlier jenkins were failing on previous patch set because of following issue:

Recently patch [1] got merged which reverts changes of patch [2] in master. The patch [1] also make changes to force_delete method implementation
and the present code in master looks like this:

[i]
    def force_delete(self, context, instance):
            """Force delete an instance in any vm_state/task_state."""
            self._delete(context, instance, 'force_delete', self._do_delete,
                         task_state=task_states.DELETING)
					 
Before merging patch [2], force_delete method implemetation of master was like below code snippet (which is also same in stable/juno):

[ii]
    def force_delete(self, context, instance):	    
            """Force delete an instance in any vm_state/task_state."""
            self._delete_instance(context, instance)

The difference in both the force_delete call is, in [i] the delete_type is passed as 'force_delete' while in [ii] the delete_type is not passed hence in _delete_instnace method call, it will eventually pass delete_type as 'delete' to _delete method.

The problem with unit test is when instance vm_state is vm_states.SHELVED_OFFLOADED, then delete api calls _local_delete method and in _local_delete method it calls notify_about_instance_usage method which needs delete_type value. 

Since the actual delete_type is passed by delete-api is 'delete' but the expected delete_type is 'force_delete' hence test gets failed.

There are two approaches to resolve this issue:

a) partial backport patch [1] so that delete api get delete_type as 'force_delete' instead of 'delete' in nova/compute/api module.

Need to change only force_delete method definition (see below code snippet):

    def force_delete(self, context, instance):
            """Force delete an instance in any vm_state/task_state."""
            self._delete(context, instance, 'force_delete', self._do_delete,
                         task_state=task_states.DELETING)

b) change the delete_type from 'force_delete' to 'delete' in test_delete_forced method of nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_api module.

In patch set 2, second approach is followed to resolve the issue.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163466/3

[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121800'}, {'account_id': 1420, 'date': '2015-04-13 17:32:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Clean bdms and networks after deleting shelved VM

After deleting the shelved offloaded instance with user volumes,
the bdms and networks info should be cleanup. This patch use local
deleting to cleanup the instance info.

(cherry picked from commit 54f4600c82241ad6ae6768d3dcd1e1755dac4ddc)
Conflicts:
	nova/compute/api.py
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_api.py

Closes-bug: #1307791
change-Id: Id32385df5b20903d7a019c3590432f3fb1133f90

commit_message:
VMware: better exception handling

Commit 1668fef9cabea6a23023aab6b97617b4368b14d6 corrected many
wrongs that we have with the oslo.vmware exceptions. The problem
is that that patch broke nova. This patch addresses the code in
Nova to enable it to upgrade to a oslo.vmware package that has
better exception handling.

The patch does the following:
1. Ensures that place that treated VMwareDriverException will also
   treat VimFaultException. This will ensure that the code is backward
   and forward compatible
2. Fixes unit tests to ensure the above

Note: I have tested the code with oslo.vmware 0.13.0

Closes-Bug: #1459021

Change-Id: I8da60c8e31aad83f75218a3c9d49a7cd515f47f2

commit_message:
Adding paramiko injections check to blacklist functions

This commit adds a check for paramiko.exec_command, as it sends
the command directly to shell, and may be vulnerable to a command
injection vulnerability if called with untrusted input.  This
commit also checks paramiko.invoke_shell, which may be similarly
vulnerable.

Change-Id: I51ce997073eae94c910483790f172afdbf407e7e

commit_message:
Fixes nova rescue / unrescue

Removes extra argument passed to _create_root_vhd by the rescue_instance
method.
Fixes the arguments passed from driver to vmops for unrescue.
Avoids deletion of 'None' file during unrescue.

Change-Id: I1636783c2681392654c6a3fcf7dd0997d6b46e1b
(cherry picked from commit f106b6ed78a7aca688e72ca1ec094867dee1a547)

commit_message:
The devref for Nova stable API

This document describes the expect of Nova REST API from Nova team. Also can
resolve some confuse what you see in the current Nova code. The Nova team will
try to reach the final goal of this document described.

Co-Authored-By: Jay Pipes <jaypipes@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ia837bca561fa8a7c48eadfcd9bd791dc8c8d29ac

commit_message:
Removing unnecessary test setting of dashboards

HORIZON_CONFIG is still being used to set default values for
dashboards and default_dashboard. This method of specifying these
is deprecated. All of these default behaviors are now covered in
the enabled directory. Removing them to remove seeing the
deprecation warning every time tests run.

Closes-Bug: #1466671
Change-Id: Ifd833288f0bf2992bd810a93a74a799232f119ab

commit_message:
Pass proxy environment variables to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox fails even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fixes this problem by passing (upper case and lower case)
http_proxy, https_proxy and no_proxy from environment to tox.

See: commit 2d02ebb775ec44a14e325c56d4a901c5705fbb94

Change-Id: Ib7964fd5ea4fb8398cdb4cd94a70fe7fae49f973

commit_message:
[Manila] Add scenario for creation/deletion of Manila share networks

List of changes:
- Added support of 'create' and 'delete' operations for share networks.
- Added benchmark for creating and deleting share networks.

Change-Id: I25ffb2d8d769f6d81972f8773951246f11abb2a0

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-15 16:43:27.000000000', 'message': "Fix Python 3 issues in tests.api.v2

* CombinationEvaluator: on Python 3, convert states (built using zip) to
  a list because states is consumed more than once. On Python 3, zip()
  returns an iterator which can only be consumed once.
* HTTP body is a bytes string: fix unit tests to use bytes instead of
  native string (Unicode on Python 3).
* test_alarm_scenarios: format key and value representation at runtime
  instead of using hardcoded value because repr(u'abc) doesn't start
  with u'...' prefix anymore on Python 3.
* Replace dict.keys()[0] with list(dict.keys())[0]. On Python 3, keys()
  returns an iterator which is not indexable.
* test_list_meters_scenarios: base64.encodestring() returns a byte
  string whereas the test expects a native string (so Unicode on
  Python 3). On Python 3, decode the string from ASCII to get Unicode.
* AggregatorTransformer: replace dict.values() with list(dict.values())
  to get a copy of the list of values on Python 3, instead of a view
  (still connected to the dictionary).
* Add the following tests of ceilometer.tests.api.v2 to tox -e py34:

  - test_alarm_scenarios.TestAlarms.test_alarms_query_with_timestamp
  - test_complex_query
  - test_complex_query_scenarios.TestQueryMetersController.test_query_with_isotime

Note: The test_list_meters_scenarios and test_statistics_scenarios tests
of ceilometer.tests.api.v2 cannot be executed by testtools.run.

Change-Id: I8258c2d17fbc1236f4bcda40bff93a93bddf13e2

  native string (Unicode on Python 3).
* test_alarm_scenarios: format key and value representation at runtime
  instead of using hardcoded value because repr(u'abc) doesn't start
  with u'...' prefix anymore on Python 3.
* Replace dict.keys()[0] with list(dict.keys())[0]. On Python 3, keys()
  returns an iterator which is not indexable.
* test_list_meters_scenarios: base64.encodestring() returns a byte
  string whereas the test expects a native string (so Unicode on
  Python 3). On Python 3, decode the string from ASCII to get Unicode.
* AggregatorTransformer: replace dict.values() with list(dict.values())
  to get a copy of the list of values on Python 3, instead of a view
  (still connected to the dictionary).
* Add the following tests of ceilometer.tests.api.v2 to tox -e py34:

  - test_alarm_scenarios.TestAlarms.test_alarms_query_with_timestamp
  - test_complex_query
  - test_complex_query_scenarios.TestQueryMetersController.test_query_with_isotime
  - test_list_resources_scenarios.TestListResources.test_with_invalid_resource_id

* test_list_meters_scenarios: decode JSON data (HTTP body) from UTF-8.
  json.loads() requires Unicode on Python 3.

Note: The test_list_meters_scenarios and test_statistics_scenarios tests
of ceilometer.tests.api.v2 cannot be executed by testtools.run.

Change-Id: I8258c2d17fbc1236f4bcda40bff93a93bddf13e2

commit_message:
Fix unicode/bytes issues in API v2 tests

* HTTP body type is bytes: fix tests to use bytes strings.
* test_list_resources_scenarios: on Python 3, base64.encodestring() returns
  bytes whereas the test expects bytes; decode the result from ASCII.
* tox.ini: add the following API v2 tests to Python 3.4:

  - test_alarm_scenarios.TestAlarms.test_alarms_query_with_timestamp
  - test_complex_query_scenarios.TestQueryMetersController.test_query_with_isotime
  - test_list_resources_scenarios.TestListResources.test_with_invalid_resource_id

Change-Id: I8258c2d17fbc1236f4bcda40bff93a93bddf13e2

commit_message:
Fix up README to work with the release tools

Add links to the bug tracker and source in a way the release script can
find them.

Move the contributing instructions to a separate file, where github will
pick them up and the release tools won't be confused by the urls.

Change-Id: Icbc1fdde3245ef6aa750bd44601adb1514763034

commit_message:
Add 'docker' to the list of known hypervisor types

nova-docker is out of tree, but it's starting to be used by people, and
being able to use a docker-specific hypervisor type can be quite useful
(in mixed-hypervisor environments, for instance).

Change-Id: I5a50de6bf73372f1ab999fd977aa58b33ffacfb9
(cherry picked from commit 2a21fcd073b44eb32f821fe3eb938dba7c34f6bc)

commit_message:
Add a scenario test for default route behavior

This test ensures that internet is available for an instance only if an
internet gateway is set as the default router.

Change-Id: Iadcf23c89e01bdf63002033c95615ee1e3f9f31d

commit_message:
Running with 'LIBS_FROM_GIT=pbr' causes failure

If you have 'pbr' in your LIBS_FROM_GIT list, then the following error
occurs:

+ cd /opt/stack/requirements
/home/ubuntu/devstack/inc/python: line 229: cd: /opt/stack/requirements:
No such file or directory

This is due to commit: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192494 moving
the clone of 'requirements' after 'setup_lib "pbr"' - which depends
on the directory existing.

The fix is to move the clone back before the pbr section,
leaving the pip_install for afterwards.

Change-Id: I04bd887d3c8157533f79cb737d040a5803c7a9dd
Closes-Bug: #1466577

commit_message:
Strip markers from test requirements.

Setuptools doesn't [yet] support markeres in tests_require parameters
to setup(). While we need to get that fixed, we also need to support
syncing marker constrained requirements from global-requirements.

Since version constraints are needed to successfully port to Python3
this won't be a long term viable solution: but few of our test-only
dependencies require version constraints, so we can do this in the
interim. The ones that do - such as python-mysql - we're either
moving away from, or centralising them into optional dependencies
on other packages where the tests_require limitation shouldn't apply.

Change-Id: I31adaf35c8d7b72fe3f8c9242cc356fe34d537e8

commit_message:
Fix compatibility with legacy Nova client for metadata server

No test is changed because the project doesn't have tests for backward
compatibility.

commit_message:
Adding ResellerAdmin role to Ceilometer user

Swift polling requires ResellerAdmin role to be added to the
Ceilometer user. This was already added to register_endpoint.sh
so it needs to be also in os-cloud-config.

Change-Id: Ie31fe2828991e7f277b56a962de8fb0c20e5f410

commit_message:
Test if Undercloud Ceilometer monitors Overcloud

A simple test if some hardware meter has been created inside
Ceilometer. That means Ceilometer has been able to poll the
statistics from at least one Overcloud Node.

Depends on Ceilometer patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92370/

Change-Id: I0dcfa03b3aa69cc2a83566757ebcace6eb62dd16

Ladislav, I think a bit more information in the README is needed here. And perhaps the commit message as well.

If running sensors-detect is mandatory for snmpd, why do we intend to make it optional? The reasoning behind that should be in the README I think.

Or, just always run sensors-detect?

In general, I'm just missing the "why" on this change :-).'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-09 20:00:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 7585, 'date': '2014-07-25 10:47:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

James, the documentation of lm-sensors states that running sensors detect is mandatory. Though when I just yum install lm-sensors, I don't have to run it and the sensor stats are there.

So it is there if we will need it, you will just allow it by pass-trough mechanism. I don't have that many hardware around to test if there are actually all sensors detected or we need to run it.

Plus running it on some hardware could break things, so it should be up to people to decide whether to run it. I think 'read man sensors-detect' is verbose enough. :-)

If you could help me with rephrasing it to be more understandable, I would appreciate."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 10:48:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Allowing to optionally run sensors-detect

Allowing to optionally run sensors-detect feature in lm-sensors.
If passing run_sensors_detect parameter through heat, sensors-detect
will be invoked with default input.
According to documentation this step is mandatory, though sensors
might be visible after installing lm-sensors without running detect.

Change-Id: I8e361b60fce8215d0e4666c8c38c86985dda8261

commit_message:
Switch to os-cloud-config register-endpoints

Switching to os-cloud-config register-endpoints. Changing interface
to new one.

Endpoints will be created exatly the same as before, so this change
is backwards compatible.

Roles are created as part of register endpoints now.

Depends on:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/132983/
Without this patch there is failure while uploading image
using Overcloud Glance.

Change-Id: I90c5fd909459e2e41641fd49ce6ea00cc554de8e

MOS-RN6.1 Keystone resolved issues

Adds Keystone resolved issue to the MOS 6.1
Release Notes page:

- keystone doesn't respond if cluster is actively used.

I would have preferred you imported xrange from six instead of range, but that's just me. :)"}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-06-10 19:50:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)

Moving xrange to range is great, but there's no value in using six.moves.range over the new builtin range.

The only thing this helps with is for is performance in cases where we're stuck on python 2.  My vote would be to either:
1. suck it up and just use range() everywhere
2. Wait for this change until the "last" python 3 change and just set everything to range() then

Anyway, I'm very anti-six wherever possible.'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-06-10 21:48:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-11 10:22:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> I would have preferred you imported xrange from six instead of range, but that's just me. :)

I prefer to write code which looks like Python 3 code. In Python 3, there is no more xrange. IMO "range" is more readable than "xrange" (what is this X?).

In Python 3, there is no function to create a list of integers like Python 2 range. range() is always an efficient iterator. Adding "from six.moves import range" makes the code behave the same on Python 2 and Python 3, it avoids bad surprises when running the code on Python 3.

The only risk is to get bug if the code really expected a list, but I rely on the large test suite to detect such bug. In other projets, I found and fixed such code. I didn't find such code in Cinder.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-11 10:25:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

John Griffith:
> Moving xrange to range is great, but there's no value in using six.moves.range over the new builtin range.

I don't want to take the responsability of adding a performance regression in Cinder. If you guess that using range() on Python 2 has no impact on performances (or you have a benchmark to check performances), I would prefer to do that in a separated patch based on mine. Or maybe write a patch replacing xrange with range in the current code."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 11:41:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Replace xrange() with six.moves.range()

Add "from six.moves import range" to replace the builtin range()
function with six.moves.range() to always create an iterator, instead of
creating a temporary list.

Replace "xrange" with "range".

Don't add the import for ranges of 1024 items or less.

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: If618b4e810e444f7eb6592bb2398805e9d14d548

There are some changes coming to way alarm evaluation works, see the summit etherpad at https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/ceilometer-alarm-and-log-improvments . Most of the approaches discussed would require DB access for caching anyway.

So I agree that the alarm evaluator needs some form of DB access. I think the reason it was implemented via HTTP API is that the alarm evaluator is considered to be sort of orthogonal to Ceilometer, even though it currently lives in the Ceilometer code tree. Using HTTP API makes sense for accessing some other project's data, but alarms are the *evaluator*'s data, nobody else's. 

Samples, on the other hand, aren't evaluator's data. I don't necessarily think using the storage layer to compute statistics is a good way to go, since it was pointed out by Eoghan at the summit session that the API layer can provide additional functionality, such as complex queries, selectable aggregates, etc. Looking at the code though, the API layer mostly does validation and the functionality is available in the storage layer directly. So this is up to debate and which way the core developers decide to take the alarm evaluator."}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2014-05-26 12:13:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Nejc Saje, thanks for your detailed comments.

1.thanks for let me know the probable tendency, I will try to learn more about this.

2. With the perspective of Ceilometer code tree, the alarm-part of db implementation will may be separated from ceilometer/storage to ceilometer/alarm/storage for BP:https://review.openstack.org/#/c/94829/. 

3.absolutely agree with you, currently, the complex queries, selectable aggregates actually are directly implemented  base on database layer, the API just do some parameter validation and parameter sanitizing. as my previous understanding, I think the storage functions base (storage/base.py) have defined a uniform db API. So it is better to pay attention to more thoughts:)'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-05-26 12:19:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
libvirt: adjust test_get_disk_bus test to ImageMetaProps object

test_get_disk_bus test is incompatible with the new
ImageMetaProps object, as None values for the hw_cdrom_bus field
are not allowed.
Adjusting the test to not set the properties instead,
as it has the same effect.

Change-Id: I1ef5c235fcf7fbc3f2780c3b93344c9506b952f7

commit_message:
objects: raise a meaningful exception when validating VIF properties

Raise an UnsupportedVIFModel exception in the fields object
when validating the VIF values.

This will allow to re-raise a meaningful exception.

Closes-Bug: #1463655
Change-Id: I5dadfbfa1a7970977cffaa63a4cbff663edb7197

commit_message:
libvirt: adjust os_command_empty test to ImageMetaProps object

test_get_guest_config_os_command_empty is incompatible with the new
ImageMetaProps object, as empty values are not for os_command_line field
are not allowed.
Adjusting the test to test against an empty image properties, instead of
an empty vaule, as it has the same effect.

Closes-Bug: #1463651
Change-Id: I5f493e3d923544498dde22ee92d83d71460767e1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-12 11:35:20.000000000', 'message': "Fix Python 3 issues in utils

* Replace string.split(key_file, ',') with key_file.split(','):
  the string.split() function was removed in Python 3, use the
  str.split() method instead
* Fix conf_fixture: import backup_enable_progress_timer and
  backup_swift_enable_progress_timer options
* hash_file(): use b'' (bytes) for the sentinel, not '' (unicode), when
  reading the input binary file
* test_hash_file() requires a binary file (bytes), not a text file
  (unicode)
* Get the builtin open() function from six.moves.builtins instead of
  getting it from __builtin__ to mock the open() function. The
  __builtin__ module was renamed to builtins in Python 3.
* sanitize_hostname(): on Python 3, decode back the hostname from Latin1
  to work on a native string (Unicode)
* replace reduce() with six.moves.reduce(): the Python 2 builtin
  reduce() function was moved to the functools module in Python 3
* convert_version_to_str(): fix integer division, use a//b, not a/b
* convert_version_to_str(): replace reduce() with ''.join() with map(str)

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: If7b8f50c6a8b0a5044c2c7108b2b0293dddafff3

commit_message:
Fix Python 3 issues in utils

* Replace string.split(key_file, ',') with key_file.split(','):
  the string.split() function was removed in Python 3, use the
  str.split() method instead
* Fix conf_fixture: import backup_enable_progress_timer and
  backup_swift_enable_progress_timer options. This change is required
  to run tests using testtools (it's now possible yet to run tests on
  Python 3 using testr).
* hash_file(): use b'' (bytes) for the sentinel, not '' (unicode), when
  reading the input binary file
* test_hash_file() requires a binary file (bytes), not a text file
  (unicode)
* Get the builtin open() function from six.moves.builtins instead of
  getting it from __builtin__ to mock the open() function. The
  __builtin__ module was renamed to builtins in Python 3.
* sanitize_hostname(): on Python 3, decode back the hostname from Latin1
  to work on a native string (Unicode)
* replace reduce() with six.moves.reduce(): the Python 2 builtin
  reduce() function was moved to the functools module in Python 3
* convert_version_to_str(): fix integer division, use a//b, not a/b
* convert_version_to_str(): replace reduce() with ''.join() with map(str)

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: If7b8f50c6a8b0a5044c2c7108b2b0293dddafff3

commit_message:
Close connections from SegmentedIterable on client disconnection

SegmentedIterable is used to retrieve segments from DLO and SLO objects. When
a client disconnect during the download of a segment, the connection to the
object server is not closed.

This commit add a close() method to SegmentedIterable that is called on a
client disconnection. Thus, proxy server does not leak connections anymore.

Change-Id: I598fb7c50f626bb065f70f62b6f9d32d6b18749f
Closes-Bug: #1466549

I'm not sure about this one, presumably folks used the L suffix for some reason or another (or maybe not, I dunno)....

But; while it's great that python3 treats everything as a Long, and some brain dead individual couldn't just keep the syntax valid and ignore it...  Ok... no ranting... sorry.

My point is, for systems running on 2.X still, they may have made these Longs for a reason and this patch breaks that.

The alternative would be our own long() util that "does the right thing" after checking version info.

I dont' know if anybody cares or not, but we should be careful IMO.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-06-10 20:55:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Ok... there are only two occurences.  The one in the HP code shouldn't even be there anyway and they don't appear to be using it specifically as a long anyway.

I'll let Xing vote on the EMC case"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-10 21:52:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

John Griffith:
> I'm not sure about this one, presumably folks used the L suffix for some reason or another (or maybe not, I dunno).

In the patch, I don't see any function where the exact type (int or long) matters.

I saw code relying on the exact type in other projects, like serialization code, or more generally coding dispatching on the type. It's important to ensure that the long type is still testesd on Python 2.

But I don't see such code in my patch.

> The alternative would be our own long() util that "does the right thing" after checking version info.

When I ported code to Python 3, sometimes I used "if six.PY2:" to add a code specific to Python 2 to handle the long type, which doesn't exist anymore in Python 3. I don't think that an helper is required in cinder.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-11 16:47:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-11 16:47:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Drop L suffix from long integers

Replace 123L with 123 to make Cinder code compatible with Python 3.

This patch was generated by the long operation of the sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* hp_3par_common: bump version

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I3086d3e3d9c3ede358313bdd43d1eee9cfdafe15

Thanks for taking this up. 

I was triaging a couple of similar downstream bugs that hit this EBUSY error code and where QEMU ends up in a defunct state. Dan Berrange helped with the below rationale (similar to what he notes in the upstream bug):

"The EBUSY error code is actually one that's reported by libvirt when the process fails to die in an acceptable amount of time. The EBUSY isn't directly related to anything in the OS / storage stack.

There are two reasons why this might happen

 - The host is so overloaded that the kernel was not able to clean up the process in the time that libvirt was prepared to wait. If this is the case, the process should eventually go away on its own after a short while longer and everything should return to normal

 - There is some problem, causing the process to get stuck in an uninterruptable wait state. This is usually due to something going wrong in the storage stack, causing some I/O read/write operation to hang in kernel space. In this case the process will stay around in the zombie state forever, or until the storage problem is resolved.

Assuming the defunct process is not going away of its own accord, it sounds like the second scenario is more likely here. This isn't really a bug in the shutdown / reboot call in nova or libvirt  - there's nothing they can do if the process is stuck in kernel space"'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-11 16:36:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Blarg, looks like this isn't helping:

http://goo.gl/D7drzq"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-06-11 08:44:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So there are two reasons why you'd get this failure from libvirt. The first is simply that the host is overloaded and so the kernel doesn't clean up qemu in time. The second is that there is some kind of storage failure causing QEMU to get stuck in kernelspace in an uninterruptable I/O operation. In this case no amounting of killing QEMU will work - it requires unblocking of the storage I/O to let it go.  Since we've now waited 90 seconds it seems unlikely to be the first reason and more likely to be storage related."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-06-11 12:23:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I've been looking at the change here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179689/34

which exhibits a job with the EBUSY error. What's fun is that the job showing this error actually ended up with a Success status not failed :-)

http://logs.openstack.org/89/179689/34/check/check-tempest-dsvm-centos7/c7fb267/

Taking the nova log

http://logs.openstack.org/89/179689/34/check/check-tempest-dsvm-centos7/c7fb267/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz

We see the instance start


2015-06-11 01:48:01.322 INFO nova.compute.manager [req-8b49b17b-0473-408b-8c40-aaaeddcc4822 None None] [instance: bc7a8641-d99f-4981-84c8-536cbc231382] VM Started (Lifecycle Event)

Then we try terminating it

2015-06-11 01:48:10.322 INFO nova.compute.manager [req-9794c663-8f3b-476c-b3b2-5cf16593051a ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1049499083 ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1148490304] [instance: bc7a8641-d99f-4981-84c8-536cbc231382] Terminating instance


We see 3 failed attempts

2015-06-11 01:48:25.360 WARNING nova.virt.libvirt.driver [req-9794c663-8f3b-476c-b3b2-5cf16593051a ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1049499083 ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1148490304] [instance: bc7a8641-d99f-4981-84c8-536cbc231382] Error from libvirt during destroy. Code=38 Error=Failed to terminate process 16884 with SIGKILL: Device or resource busy; attempt 1 of 3

2015-06-11 01:48:40.592 WARNING nova.virt.libvirt.driver [req-9794c663-8f3b-476c-b3b2-5cf16593051a ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1049499083 ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1148490304] [instance: bc7a8641-d99f-4981-84c8-536cbc231382] Error from libvirt during destroy. Code=38 Error=Failed to terminate process 16884 with SIGKILL: Device or resource busy; attempt 2 of 3


2015-06-11 01:48:55.627 WARNING nova.virt.libvirt.driver [req-9794c663-8f3b-476c-b3b2-5cf16593051a ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1049499083 ServerRescueNegativeTestJSON-1148490304] [instance: bc7a8641-d99f-4981-84c8-536cbc231382] Error from libvirt during destroy. Code=38 Error=Failed to terminate process 16884 with SIGKILL: Device or resource busy; attempt 3 of 3


This bc7a8641-d99f-4981-84c8-536cbc231382 uuid corresponds to instance-0000004d. So looking at the QEMU log file for that

http://logs.openstack.org/89/179689/34/check/check-tempest-dsvm-centos7/c7fb267/logs/libvirt/qemu/instance-0000004d.txt.gz

I see the startup marker which corresponds to the timestamp nova has

2015-06-11 01:48:01.084+0000: starting up

What is interesting is the shutdown marker

qemu: terminating on signal 15 from pid 12032
2015-06-11 01:50:08.097+0000: shutting down

Notice that this is another 75 seconds after Nova's attempt 3 failed. 

So the time we started termination to the time it actually succeeded was 2 minutes, but we only waited for 45 seconds (3 attempts * 15 seconds).

I looked in syslog but didn't see any obvious storage related errors

So perhaps the gate system really is that slow. Which would suggest you need to make the max attempts much much longer - perhaps 10, or even 15 attempts, which would give 150 seconds or 225 seconds."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-06-11 12:45:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

While the nodes used in the gate are slow, we don't *usually* hit any hardware bottlnecks. To confirm this we run dstat:

http://logs.openstack.org/89/179689/34/check/check-tempest-dsvm-centos7/c7fb267/logs/screen-dstat.txt.gz"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-06-11 13:29:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Looking at the dstat I'm not seeing much that jumps out at me as being unreasonable. Memory usage is fairly high, but there's always at least 150 MB free. There's a wide variety of processes show as top CPU & top I/O, but none for a prolonged period of time. THere's often plenty of CPU idle time too. Its all very puzzelling, unless the physical host is not scheduling the 1st level VM sufficiently, but that's seems unlikely."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-06-11 14:54:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

We could try increasing the timeout.  Tempest has it's own timeout for state transitions, but I think it's currently 5 minutes so that shouldn't affect us here if increasing to 2 minutes or so would help."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-06-15 13:54:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Interesting, when we hit attempt 3 of 3 and still pass, it's only happening on centos 7 / fc21 jobs:

http://goo.gl/JMtH5S

That suggests there is something working better in newer versions of qemu/libvirt here.  Maybe we could change the timeouts based on libvirt version?"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-06-15 13:58:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The CentOS 7.1 job has libvirt 1.2.8 and the fc21 job has libvirt 1.2.9.'}, {'account_id': 6962, 'date': '2015-06-19 11:05:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Cherry Picked

This patchset was cherry picked to branch stable/kilo as commit bc9b86405c79c2da42ab1ae2e152ba89969b0d02'}]

commit_message:
libvirt: handle code=38 + sigkill (ebusy) in destroy()

Handle the libvirt error during destroy when the sigkill fails due to an
EBUSY. This is taken from a comment by danpb in the bug report as a
potential workaround.

Co-authored-by: Daniel Berrange (berrange@redhat.com)

Closes-Bug: #1353939

Change-Id: I128bf6b939fbbc85df521fd3fe23c3c6f93b1b2c

commit_message:
Reattach the original configdrive during unrescue

At the moment, the instance original configdrive is not reattached
when the instance is unrescued. This behavior can be undesired.

This patch fixes the issue by reattaching the instance configdrive
during the unrescue operation, in case it exists.

Change-Id: I82e2b31139d947a4201c770db37d84b83bba282a
(cherry picked from commit 3a2b460c1e552812c8e7694954c12dfe3b9e3a97)

commit_message:
Reattach the original configdrive during unrescue

At the moment, the instance original configdrive is not reattached
when the instance is unrescued. This behavior can be undesired.

This patch fixes the issue by reattaching the instance configdrive
during the unrescue operation, in case it exists.

Change-Id: I82e2b31139d947a4201c770db37d84b83bba282a

commit_message:
Fixes nova rescue / unrescue

Removes extra argument passed to _create_root_vhd by the rescue_instance
method.
Fixes the arguments passed from driver to vmops for unrescue.
Avoids deletion of 'None' file during unrescue.

Change-Id: I1636783c2681392654c6a3fcf7dd0997d6b46e1b

commit_message:
Use UPLINK net type instead of LOCAL

Previously, 'LOCAL' network type was used to determine whether a
Neutron network is an uplink network or not. This caused a problem in
Neutron because, following the behavior of ML2, all external networks
when 'providernet' extension is enabled usually have a type, and
typically configured to have 'LOCAL' as the default, unless explicitly
specified, making it impossible to differentiate uplink and external
networks.  To get around it, this patch defines a new type 'UPLINK' to
replace 'LOCAL'.  Also, instead of validating against the unsupported
types, just log and continue.  This way, 'providernet' extension could
continue to be used with Horizon, until it is patched to accept uplink
type.

Change-Id: Ifb0dbe8d2c86456b11064c786f8ebe6e4126d206
Implements: MNP-150

commit_message:
Make test_rest keystone cache work with keystonemiddleware 2.0

Token cache keys in keystonemiddleware 2.0 are sha256 hashes of the
token key. This is _not_ the case in keystonemiddleware <2.0. This
change adjusts the FakeMemcache to support both types of key.

keystonemiddleware also breaks WebTest linting, so turn that off
until there has been progress on fixing that.

Change-Id: I28b5dbfbc915d424c74993732ddc041e528903e6

I have a few minor things inline that I'd like to see fixed up.  BUT most importantly I need/want to be able to actually run this to better figure some things out.

As it stands, the process of trying to install and run in devstack is... well.... not easy at all.  In fact even with your help I've had one semi successful config/run.  I realize that all of the deps and weirdness in the devstack plugin side are causing some of the problems.

I'd propose we merge the changes, see if it solves some of the CI issues I've been running into (I think it will) and go from there.  Some of the issues I've run into include failure to delete volumes (reported as deleted, deleted in Cinder but still on the backend... at which point the system starts to slow to a crawl and things start failing).  Looking at what you're running in the gate patch this isn't a problem so it's either my config/setup or something to do with me getting a bad merge on the driver patch when I pull it in?

Anyway... I vote we land this with a probation statement to aid in deploy and test."}, {'account_id': 16258, 'date': '2015-06-15 21:03:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

commit_message:
Re-add DRBD driver

This reverts commit 37eef0b3d4d786d4b2b1a7e48f3e2339506e85e2.

We hope to have a -infra CI running by June 12th, to get included
in Liberty.

Change-Id: Icb7347d55dc5b22720269405b6d2b4053c2ad819

commit_message:
6.1 -- Consume External Ubuntu

Add instructions on how change a path for
Ubuntu system packages.
Add to new features that the Ubuntu
system packages can now be downloaded
from official Ubuntu mirrors or
from internal repos.

Change-Id: Ic0bc99a5d0af7c0e870509f77df17c311cf56b90

commit_message:
Ensure tests run under python2.7

tox uses whatever python version that tox ran with as the default python
version for environments (py27,py3x, etc are given a more specific
default).

Debian's python-tox (for example) uses python3, but we require python2.7
- and a naive `apt-get install python-tox; tox -epep8` fails with
py3-related errors on Debian.

This change explicitly sets `basepython = python2.7` in several testing
environments that would otherwise have used the default basepython.

Change-Id: I377ac6d72dec5b85c105d8a1a74f6974efb84dcf

commit_message:
Added priorities for centos repos

We need to be able to download packages from
various repositories taking into account repository
priority. We need this for patching story.

This patch introduces MULTI_MIRROR_CENTOS variable
which is supposed to have the following format:

  "name1,url1,pri1 name2,url2,pri2"

In case when pri is not defined it will be set to 10,
for example
  "name1,url1"
        is equal to:
  "name1,url1,10"

Besides, this patch introduces uniformity for all those
cases USE_MIRROR=msk|srt|none removing unused variables.

It is supposed that USE_MIRROR=none is only used for
building Centos mirror not for building ISO.

Change-Id: I84a893a32194f0d6f5c2727af373f680fae1aaae
Closes-Bug: #1446293

I'd like to talk about this review more at the weekly meeting. While I understand the desire to have a single global variable to control certain aspects of the deployment I don't agree that the roles themselves need any specific global variable as a simplified override. Every role has a namespaced variables to ensure separation between roles. In the Juno/Icehouse releases we used a lot of global variables and it was architecturally limiting and I'd like very much not to go down that path again. Sure this means having to set more variables for a given deployment however it's also more precise."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-16 10:34:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Implement service_region user_group_var

Currently each service has an individual service_region var
which needs to be set when setting up a region that is
different to the default.

This patch implements a user_group_var called 'service_region'
which can be used to set the region for all services.

The AIO bootstrap script is also altered to set the
service_region in the user config.

Change-Id: I5ed216916f667506ffed900a01744dad973221bf
Closes-Bug: #1463366

commit_message:
Update rabbitmq to v3.5.3-1

This change updates rabbitmq to the latest stable rabbitmq release
the new version is v3.5.3-1 and is being done to ensure that we are
maintaining a stable release with updated bug fixes and patches.

Change-Id: I6d8a367a896194d3a1f8f64fc04e08a06078d1ec
(cherry picked from commit f9febc97b289c36b4396783558d4eaba38f78b81)

- os-ansible-deployment-dsvm-check-commit http://logs.openstack.org/48/192148/2/check/os-ansible-deployment-dsvm-check-commit/fecac86/ : SUCCESS in 50m 46s'}, {'account_id': 14552, 'date': '2015-06-17 14:30:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I see an issue where we set the service protocol for all endpoint types at the same time and this is not what we do in reality. publicURL endpoints are only SSL, all other types, internal and adminURL as in HTTP only. Having this requirement, we need to be able to choose the service protocol per endpoint type. I don't think someone will ever need a protocol per endpoint type per service.
So I would vote to separate public from all the other endpoints"}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-06-17 18:26:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

This is a cherry-pick from master. as such +2 as is. 

Per @Bjoern's I disagree that you need anything else to make what you're looking for possible. You can set something like ``nova_service_publicuri`` to whatever you need or want. You will need to do this per service within a role/set of variables however forcing the deployer to perform that interaction means that the deployer should be acutely aware of what is being configured and how."}, {'account_id': 14552, 'date': '2015-06-18 18:16:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Kevin, I disagree. The default configuration should be safe and sane. Using http as default protocol for public endpoints for example is not.
Additionally I don't want override 7 individual services * 3 endpoint types. As I proposed at bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-ansible/+bug/1399383 I like a more user friend approach."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-06-18 21:10:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Backports are not open for discussion or refactoring. Further iterations on solutions to this bug should be proposed to master and then backported in a separate review.

As for whether the default should be http or https, my opinion is split. For one, secure by default is always the better option. That said, if TLS is turned on but no certificates are provided, you're gaining no security. If the deployer needs certificates for these services to talk to each other internally then that is not user friendly. If we generate a bunch of self-signed certs but the clients all use insecure=False then again, you're getting no security. This is all a different discussion that should happen on the issue."}, {'account_id': 7414, 'date': '2015-06-19 08:38:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Totes agree with Ian.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-19 08:38:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.

commit_message:
Allow protocol to be set per endpoint-type

If services are running behind an SSL terminating LB you will want to
differentiate between protocol on internalURL and publicURL endpoints.
This patch allows you to set the values of protocol per endpoint type,
but doesn't change the default behaviour which is to have it set in one
var.

Change-Id: I7a74c85a8841499623746586ae27103a71c6fec0
Partial-Bug: #1399383
(cherry picked from commit 1a2907c6a137bc4bc110f971f34904a20a7a5ad4)

commit_message:
Nodes metadata filtration added

Filtering of private nodes metadata added to statsender.
This patchset is only for syncronization of code in stable/6.1 and master.
Current whitelists implementation is not fit to fix this issue due to
meatdata data structure. Filtration by whitelists is going to be implemened
in: https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1466121

Change-Id: I2c5f39e0ac0f77c281db444933ac54723c2645c7
Closes-Bug: #1466140

commit_message:
Split environment file into component parts

This patch splits the monolithic openstack_environment file
into component parts, making them easier to understand and
manipulate.

Change-Id: I45887599bd887a272798047f9ad650d4811ab380
Closes-Bug: #1463862
(cherry picked from commit ecf77297955922d31dfaa3e6570bd6589f759b2f)

@afazekas - Thanks for review.

Actually all schema has been modified to work for all extension (as current tests runs for all extension enable).

As v2 (v2.1) API are frozen, tempest should have additionalProperties False to capture any unwanted changes in those API.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-03-18 13:07:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines

"Adding a property to a resource representation" is generally acceptable.

"Changing or removing a property in a resource representation"
OR "Changing the semantics of a property in a resource representation which may be supplied by clients" is generally not acceptable.

We do not need to prevent additional properties.'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-03-19 22:22:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31:

Yea, those are acceptable and it used to done by adding new extension etc.
But as v2 nd v2.1 are frozen and no new extension for thosse. All new attributes etc can be added with microversion only. As it is done for first microversion - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/140313/

Please do let me know if m missing anything on this.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-03-20 01:00:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Code-Review+2

Yeah, Ghanshyam is right.

As http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-February/057613.html , new attributes will be added with microversions and v2(v2.1) should be frozen.

commit_message:
Block additionalProperties on Nova API tests

Now Nova team is allowing additional properties with microversions
only, that means Nova v2 and v2.1 should not contain additional
properties forever. In addition, we should not allow vender-specific
properties for OpenStack interoperability.
This patch disables additionalProperties for blocking such properties
for v2 and v2.1 API.

Change-Id: Ica929c402a3d042ae751302384e68853eb28b405

commit_message:
Fixed empty yaml load

This change fixes the py_pkgs plugin so that if the plugin loads an empty file
or if there is an exception raised when loading the contents of a yaml file
the item will be skipped and no bad data will be passed onto the rest of the
plugin.

Change-Id: Ica3af42d95e7f3140e437e388b25f41bc14db47f
Closes-Bug: #1464673

commit_message:
Dynamic index.rst for specs

Build doc/source/index.rst dynamically based on the subdirectories in specs/
directory that correspond to release version numbers. This allows to submit
specs for new releases without manually creating a toctree.

Header and footer templates added for building doc/source/index.rst file.

Change-Id: I1985c1e770be3430a3699832d7b5b056dbf1faa9

commit_message:
Stop Haproxy listen to 35357 for public.

Stop Haproxy listen to 35357 port on public
interface. Admin endpoint should not be exposed on public.

Change-Id: Ic86f940de7ad18ac5bde528f3fb88f64e11a48e5

commit_message:
Revert "Change default IO scheduler to deadline"

This reverts commit ec917ae36d2a1b482b189f29483cfdbc5ce700be.

As shown by simple benchmark on Launchpad report[1], the change has decreased the performance.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1418126/comments/14

Change-Id: I087952152ff522c343bb209413c9905b2d4b1f29

commit_message:
Increase threshold for running processes for zabbix

Modern OS can run much more than 300 processes, so zabbix warns every
time about it. Increased value to 500.

Change-Id: Icbcfa2009e312a66c84f3de5f16b53c95052553b
Closes-Bug: #1434118

commit_message:
Do not add @domain_name to dnsmasq.conf if it equals 'local'

Currently dnsmasq tries to resolve locally a host named
test.mydomain.local instead of forwarding this request to the local dns
server.

Change-Id: I5892fddaffa0dc619f0a54ac0f9fac34055b9b3f
Closes-Bug: 1411425
(cherry picked from commit 3ca3ef5aae68b84ec8b9beb55e552bdd70d42599)

commit_message:
We forgot two of our cookbooks and our specs

In the move to the OpenStack namespace we forgot two of our cookbooks,
and our specs repo.

- cookbook-openstack-database
- cookbook-openstack-identity
- openstack-chef-specs

This patch brings them across for us.

Change-Id: I268a0d73dc2427db45cf5c91c6e9ee4e8b3e1d9b

commit_message:
Rename python-keystoneclient-saml2 to keystoneauth

With the ``keystoneauth`` library to be released soon we want our SAML2
authentication plugins to depend on that library, instead of
``python-keystoneclient``. For that we propose changing repository name to
``keystoneauth-saml2`` so it reflects proper hierarchy between
libraries.

This library has never had a release so will not have an impact on
users.

Change-Id: Iddf0e280c1b3513db0700c65e0f912da93119286

commit_message:
Spec to add 'libvirt_net' as vif type to novas libvirt driver.

This is required in order to attach libvirt manged kvm guests to
a libvirt managed network.

Change-Id: Ib88ad3309ae136e621545e29f301cdae51e47f60
Implements: blueprint libvirt-network-vif

commit_message:
Rectify default config values for nsx plugin

This patch corrects some values for the nsx_sync section, as well
as other configuration options used for connecting to the controller
cluster.

Change-Id: I2e70dc56c3fd493ef4b6111e4041fffc8419b856
Closes-Bug: #1465754

commit_message:
convergence: (temporary) convert int entity_id to string

We plan to change the schema of entity_id to int (as all
resource.id's are int and represent the stack.id as "0".

Until that change is done, this is a "quick fix" to make things
work.

Change-Id: I99ddc14d68b7cc0869d5bb636c06f4498344cf3d

which does not explicitly declare it.

commit_message:
Use PyMySQL in MySQL related functional/fullstack tests

mysql-python driver has been replaced by PyMySQL driver[1] in neutron
code but MySQL related functional/fullstack tests try to use
mysql-python driver because of MySQLOpportunisticTestCase[2] and tests
are skipped because mysql-python driver is no more available.

This change provides a backend implementation for mysql+pymysql, a base
base testcase MySQLTestCase[2] using mysql+pymysql implementation
(currently oslo.db provides none of them but will in the future) and
replaces MySQLOpportunisticTestCase with MySQLTestCase.

[1] I73e0fdb6eca70e7d029a40a2f6f17a7c0797a21d
[2] neutron.tests.common.base

Closes-Bug: #1463980
Change-Id: Ic5c1d12ab75443e1cc290a7447eeb4b452b4a9dd

But for icmp to work(i have two vms in two different security groups) and i have to add ingress rules in both security groups for the vm's to ping each other. However one way ping is not working just by adding ingress rule on one side
Wanted to know if there is any other patch for it to work or is this an limitation with hyperv.

Krishna"}, {'account_id': 8213, 'date': '2015-06-18 16:06:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

To answer your question, this is a limitation of Hyper-V, sadly. ICMP rules cannot be created as stateful. For ICMP, you should add both ingress and egress rules.'}, {'account_id': 16039, 'date': '2015-06-19 06:36:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V agent stateful security group rules

Hyper-V does not allow stateful ACLs with "ANY" protocol, meaning that
security group rules which allows "ANY" protocol must be split up
into separate rules for each protocol.
Also, Hyper-V does not allow stateful ICMP rules, which means ICMP rules
must be added both inbound and outbound.

Closes-Bug: #1362676

Change-Id: I0d4a6ebc6023ea616cf92539273b8b36a6b24ae0

commit_message:
Path to mysql-wss script in DB backup/restore doc

In the Fuel 6.1 Operations Guide, path to mysql-wss is incorrect in
db-backup-ops.rst file.

It is now /usr/lib/ocf/resource.d/fuel/mysql-wss, not
/usr/lib/ocf/resource.d/mirantis/mysql-wss.

Change-Id: I0aa561a9803493da45e0b023b5623f540e03de08
Closes-bug: 1464755
(cherry picked from commit a817f83b26c3a8f8dd2932a589feee5631ae96d1)

commit_message:
Add delete_network retres for v2

For plugin V2, earlier patches to have retries on error in
delete_network method was never applied.

The patches are: 0126e13 and d2fe565

Add the same retry logic for v2 in this patch.

Change-Id: I4db62889a29678f1cdccd660bb6dfc4b9d049511
Fixes: MNP-151

commit_message:
Improve Install Guide Liberty RST spec

* Properly format the RST file to make the rendered HTML look nicer.
* Change the tags to follow what is implemented.
* Mention the use of ":only:" directive.
