commit_message:
Updating Case Studies - Creating dashboard case studies

This creates case studies for both Alice and Bob in the Dashboard
chapter. This outlines Alice's work around HTST, sub domains, and
other configurations. Bob's case studies are coming, however
Alice's can be used in the meantime. Linking through the Dashboard
chapter as well.

Co-Authored-By: Dave Walker <email@daviey.com>
Change-Id: I6569d0dcb0fc6e0ba07a54e3631b58f76e5857ef
Partial-Bug: #1349540

commit_message:
remove extra_extensions config

The list of available extensions does not need to be configurable
due to a recent decision to separate the plugin packages, each of
which will have a static list of supported extensions.

This patch removes that configuration option, and adds all of the
supported extensions to the static list.

Change-Id: Ib5cf3e464bebf77815e0aa896bea187bd43b5ddf
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
Adds service_types to client_plugins

service_types is added to client_plugins to support the
conditional resource plugin availability.

implements blueprint: keystone-based-resource-availability

Change-Id: I28d606416acd1d47a09f3c62b5236b5f53583f60

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded http in URL in sahara exercise script

The script hardcoded http://$SERVICE_HOST/... which failed
when SSL or tls-proxy was enabled. Calculate the protocol
based on enabled services instead.

Change-Id: I192eeeafe7bf4dc5cbd382c505ffb9307651d78a

commit_message:
Make sure iptables-services is installed

The iptables service files are no longer included by default on
Fedora.  This causes the systemctl calls in fixup_stuff.sh to fail
when disabling firewalld in favor of iptables.

Change-Id: If37691d03e3d07ca8b53c541717081beeb184c16
Closes-Bug: #1462347

To enable a following commit to unify the `run_watchers` of

commit_message:
Remove file-driver special no-async abilities

To enable a following commit to unify the `run_watchers` of
the various drivers we need to make the file driver method
look more like the other drivers, which means removing the
special no-async ability and having it use the standard get
a future and wait on it to return (and repeat).

Change-Id: I14d227a0e6a80da80eb2580b1780ae1dba128b21

commit_message:
Add side-by-side comparison of v2 and v3 APIs

There was no document for the differences between the
v2.0 and v3 APIs.

Change-Id: Ib17ecb78d09822b5288ef82f71b433110e9a9f84
Closes-Bug: #1194885

commit_message:
neutron: remove deprecated allow_duplicate_networks config option

Commit 4306d9190f49e7fadf88669d18effedabc880d3b deprecated the
allow_duplicate_networks config option in Kilo and marked it for removal
in Liberty where the default behavior is to just allow duplicate
networks.

This simply removes the option and checks/tests around it being False.

DocImpact: Removed neutron.allow_duplicate_networks config option. The
           behavior in Liberty is now to simply allow duplicate
           networks.

Change-Id: Icb3510bcf0c30e11d0304a86ead91a43f37602ec

commit_message:
logging failed exception info for add image operation

Add image operation failed will lead to rollback operation,
delete this image if it was created.
If this operation throws some exception, previous one will be
overwritten so that we cannot elegantly trace the problem occurs.
We could log failed exception info before rollback operation.

Change-Id: Ie2efcedbd647adb827f40c2ef6673c615046c6a4
modified:   glance_store/_drivers/rbd.py

commit_message:
Make the 3PAR drivers honor the pool in create

Updated 3PAR's usage of the extra spec setting hp3par:cpg. This
setting is ignored in Kilo; the hp3par_cpg setting in cinder.conf
should be used instead.
Closes-Bug: 1434292

Change-Id: Idac6b7b2aaa04e06bc9066a38d52683da70395ee

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I7344c794b73aca1e0dcad681a4c43e3a66dd2eb3

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Iaf9247f90ba26615d02e5431d6bc98f22351caa7

commit_message:
Allow ``OS_DEBUG`` environment variable to specify log level.

Preserve original behavior when ``OS_DEBUG`` is ``True``, but if variable
is set to a valid log level, such as 'WARNING' use that level instead to
allow finer grained control over verbosity of log messages with the
FakeLogger.

Change-Id: I6594cec8de6fa221fe81f663a9126b2df8762ef3
Closes-Bug: 1280454

commit_message:
Get rid of oslo-incubator copy of middleware

We have already moved all projects away from openstack/common/middleware
modules to the oslo_middlware library. We don't need these files here
anymore.

Change-Id: I1b4cfa4a8a318d83ac107f3f631c9f1fd24178f9

[{'created': '2015-06-09 01:23:45.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "timeutils: deprecate isotime()"

This reverts commit 5cad113739fa906c3901e530fcbfdee3b48961c1.

The deprecation message says to use datetime.datetime.isoformat()
instead, but the format of the string generated by isoformat isn't
the same as the format of the string generated by isotime. The string
is used in tokens generated by keystone and other public APIs so the
format generated by isotime must continue to be used otherwise we'd
be violating the OpenStack API stability guideline. The function is
used in both keystone and keystoneclient, so if this isn't in a
common place like oslo.utils then we need to copy-paste the code
into multiple projects.

Change-Id: Iaa732bdf8597835f2422b3e984c35397e3637e01
Closes-Bug: 1461251

commit_message:
Revert "timeutils: deprecate isotime()"

This reverts commit 5cad113739fa906c3901e530fcbfdee3b48961c1.

The deprecation message says to use datetime.datetime.isoformat()
instead, but the format of the string generated by isoformat isn't
the same as the format of the string generated by isotime. The string
is used in tokens generated by keystone and other public APIs so the
format generated by isotime must continue to be used otherwise we'd
be violating the OpenStack API stability guideline. The function is
used in both keystone and keystoneclient, so if this isn't in a
common place like oslo.utils then we need to copy-paste the code
into multiple projects.

Change-Id: Iaa732bdf8597835f2422b3e984c35397e3637e01
Closes-Bug: 1461251

commit_message:
Move files into the right spot and get tests working

* Move files from keystone folder into appropriate folders
* Move tests from keystone into appropriate folders
* Fix imports to use the new module locations
* Add a _i18n.py to help with localication
* Add a BaseTestcase class
* Add a exceptions module

All just enough to run the tests. Though some tests were commented
with a FIXME to be fixed in later commits.

A few additional tests were not working with py34 and they are
skipped using testtools.skipIf statements.

commit_message:
Don't sanitize node names for log directories

The naming of nodes has recently changed so this is no longer needed. We
used to do it to strip out the random part of node names in order to
assist searching.

Change-Id: If9bdeb898016e67e873566c8bde12c8bf2d08b70

commit_message:
Python 3: do not use cmp(), nor sorted(..., cmp=...)

* The "cmp" function has been removed, so we must not use it any more;
* The "cmp" keyword argument of the "sorted" function has been removed, so
  replace it with "key=functool.cmp_to_key".

Change-Id: Ic39d29dc1002a68f36f04c32e53a36bc826dce78
Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
Remove usage of WritableLogger from oslo_log

With Eventlet 0.17.2, we can directly pass the logger
instance. This allows us to deprecate/remove the WritableLogger
class from oslo.log.

Closes-Bug: #1440773
Change-Id: I3985b30b499a1e676d39c2a6cd3a31ac13c0ab47

[{'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-05-19 02:26:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-05-19 02:28:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-19 02:30:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-keystone-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/72/184172/2/check/gate-keystone-specs-docs/7a863b1//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 21s
- gate-keystone-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/72/184172/2/check/gate-keystone-specs-python27/dee98fc/ : SUCCESS in 1m 33s'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-05-25 09:11:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2015-06-17 10:56:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Breaks on Windows, since signal.SIGUSR1 is not present:

Example: http://paste.openstack.org/show/297998/

This needs to be fixed on Olso first IMO.'}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2015-06-17 11:54:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Update: this has been fixed in Olso.incubator, but has been proposed and merged with an older oslo version on Cinder for the same blueprint, hence the issue.

Please make sure the oslo code is up to date when proposing the patch on this project.

See: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192616/'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-06-19 01:14:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

@Alessandro Pilotti,

While it is good to fix this for Windows, Keystone on windows is not officially supported. 

@liusheng,
I need to look more at what the Guru Mediation reports entail. I also would like to get direct feedback from the Security team on oslo guru mediation before we accept this into Keystone - much like the issues with osprofiler, I am worried without significantly more information, this might end up leaking sensitive data.

Once we have more information on this, we can evaluate accepting this into Keystone.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-06-19 01:17:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Please also remember that Eventlet form of Keystone is deprecated and will be removed in the next (M) release. 

This should not have any direct requirements to use greenlet or eventlet for reporting.'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-06-19 02:00:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

yeah, Morgan, thanks for clarify, I got it, abandon.'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-06-19 02:00:25.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-05-19 02:26:18.000000000', 'message': 'Adopt oslo guru meditation report to Keystone

This spec proposes adoption for Oslo Guru Meditation reports in Keystone.
The new feature will enhance debugging capabilities of all official
Keystone services, by providing an easy way to gather runtime data about
current threads and configuration, among other things, to developers,
operators, and tech support.

blueprint guru-meditation-report

commit_message:
Adopt oslo guru meditation report to Keystone

This spec proposes adoption for Oslo Guru Meditation reports in Keystone.
The new feature will enhance debugging capabilities of all official
Keystone services, by providing an easy way to gather runtime data about
current threads and configuration, among other things, to developers,
operators, and tech support.

blueprint guru-meditation-report

Change-Id: I40461f01039c2a1fa8e7f61f531f07bd23769d03

commit_message:
Enable Orchestration in DevStack

Heat is configured by default on DevStack for
Icehouse and Juno releases. Newer versions of
OpenStack require enabling Heat services in
DevStack local.conf.

Change-Id: I236178edab04999852d41590aeb2210a23c1a66f

commit_message:
Wrong config file is used for the M2 plug-in

The install-guide advises to edit the [ovs] section inside the
 /etc/neutron/plugins/ml2/ml2_conf.ini file. However, this file
 doesn't contain any [ovs] section. Instead, the install-guide
 should advise to use
 /etc/neutron/plugins/openvswitch/ovs_neutron_plugin.ini,
 which contains the section, and which should be used for
 editing the [ovs] section.

Change-Id: I7c410752b41e3f5e423bdde1f0546309f34e84a8
Closes-Bug: #1422038

Yes, you are right - 'DHCP server on the tenant network assigns itself as the DNS resolver.' In my environment it is '192.168.1.3'

Current /etc/neutron/dhcp_agent.ini in the installation guide doesn't
specify the dns-servers to be included in its configuration.

Due to this, DNS will not work in the demo-instance created in Chapter 14
because dnsmasq will not know how to handle the request in the demo-net.
ping -c openstack.org will fail without the proper forwader.

Correcting this by adding comma-separated list of DNS servers which will
be used by dnsmasq as forwarders.

Closes-Bug : #1439369

Change-Id: I9932f1c7e731a142bd097e3f35293777a397b9b3

commit_message:
Missing DNS forwarder config in subnet creation

DNS will not work in the demo-instance created in Chapter 14 because
dnsmasq will not know how to handle the request in the demo-net.
ping -c openstack.org will fail without the proper forwader.

Correcting this by adding '--dns-nameservers list=true 8.8.8.8 8.8.4.4'
to the demo subnet creation.

backport: juno icehouse
Closes-Bug: #1439369

Change-Id: I9932f1c7e731a142bd097e3f35293777a397b9b3

commit_message:
Fixes parameter order for neutron subnet-create

The order for the parameters of neturon subnet-create
is incorrect. The name of the network to which this
subnet belongs to must be placed before the CIDR.
This change fixes the placement.

Change-Id: I381e5bf66e11a6fea400737d351798033d946ae9
Closes-Bug: #1460029

commit_message:
Add step to restart rabbitmq service

Add a step to restart the rabbitmq service
to avoid problems, e.g. swift authentification with keystone.

Change-Id: Iedd915d4ab309b3b0f0267d5d38ffa1e837a8521
Closes-Bug: #1458988

commit_message:
Uncap pytz

pytz is a pretty small project without any dependencies of it's own so
it's not a transitive dependency creep risk, and Babel requires it
uncapped, so capping it in g-r is probably not a safe idea given pycadf
is using it and now has a stable/icehouse branch.

So let's uncap pytz and avoid a future gate wedge in stable/icehouse.

Change-Id: I3ca651a4377d61be3fed572355326bc180ad7eec

commit_message:
Allow default reseller prefix in domain_remap middleware

Previously, the reseller prefix needed to be provided in the host name
even when the domain was unique to that reseller. With the
default_reseller_prefix, any domain which matches in this middleware,
will will be passed on with a reseller prefix, whether or not it was
provided.

Change-Id: I5aa5ce78ad1ee2e3660cce4c3e07306f8999f02a
Implements: blueprint domainremap-reseller-domains

commit_message:
Move get_inteface_by_ip from LinuxBridge class to ip_lib

get_interface_by_ip is moved fro LinuxBridgeManager to ip_lib
as a more generic get_device_by_ip.

System-faking unit tests have been switched for functional
testing that also performs a negative test.

This can be reused in the openvswitch-agent code to validate
local_ip reusing the LinuxBridge logic.

Change-Id: I9237871a6e24dd99556c71844624be510e20d289
Related-Bug: #1464178
Related-Bug: #1408603

commit_message:
Support pushing translations to Zanata

In order to migrate to Zanata for translations, we need to modify
the proposal scripts to also upload translations to the Zanata
server. This commit supports most projects (those that make use of
upstream_translation_update.sh), as well as django_openstack_auth.

This does not impact the existing push and pull of
translations to Transifex, and also untouched are the translations
for Horizon or the manuals, which are all handled in separate scripts.

Co-Authored-By: stephane <stephane@alum.mit.edu>
Change-Id: I3bfb188c8b0c0e65f22d7edc30721b163f084fff

commit_message:
Added documentation around database upgrades

Listed the current process for upgrading the Nova database to allow for
better understanding of what will be changing.

Change-Id: Ib1c6abd8b08fe0987e2535d0ed6729f5384cebf3
Signed-off-by: Philip Schwartz <philip.schwartz@rackspace.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-06 15:41:32.000000000', 'message': 'support for keystone v3 api - add domains to service_identity

This patch implements these parts of the blueprint:

1) Adds support for domains to service_identity.
Users of this resource may specify a different domain for both the user
and the tenant/project, or may specify the default domain which will apply
to both user and tenant.  This also adds the same domain support to
keystone::endpoint since that class uses service_identity.

2) Adds a make_keystone_role_name helper method which will construct a
valid domain aware role name.  This is intended to be used in the other
puppet modules (puppet-glance) that set notifications based on
keystone_user_role resources, in order to construct valid domain aware
names for these resources.

3) Adds a new resource keystone::resource::authconfig - this manages
keystone authentication for other puppet modules by managing the
[keystone_authtoken] section in the config.  Encapsulating the
authentication configuration in this resource will ensure that we
will be able to support the several new types of authentication coming
in current and future Keystone releases.  This supports all of the
authentication options specified at:
http://www.jamielennox.net/blog/2015/02/17/loading-authentication-plugins/

3) Cleans up domain support in admin.pp and uses the new helper method

Implements: blueprint api-v3-support

Change-Id: I3d420e08c74e8a43f2431be7fd46198281438f13

commit_message:
support for keystone v3 api - add domains to service_identity

This patch implements these parts of the blueprint:

1) Adds support for domains to service_identity.
Users of this resource may specify a different domain for both the user
and the tenant/project, or may specify the default domain which will apply
to both user and tenant.  This also adds the same domain support to
keystone::endpoint since that class uses service_identity.

2) Adds a make_keystone_role_name helper method which will construct a
valid domain aware role name.  This is intended to be used in the other
puppet modules (puppet-glance) that set notifications based on
keystone_user_role resources, in order to construct valid domain aware
names for these resources.

3) Adds a new resource keystone::resource::authconfig - this manages
keystone authentication for other puppet modules by managing the
[keystone_authtoken] section in the config.  Encapsulating the
authentication configuration in this resource will ensure that we
will be able to support the several new types of authentication coming
in current and future Keystone releases.  This supports all of the
authentication options specified at:
http://www.jamielennox.net/blog/2015/02/17/loading-authentication-plugins/

4) Cleans up domain support in admin.pp and uses the new helper method

Implements: blueprint api-v3-support

Change-Id: I3d420e08c74e8a43f2431be7fd46198281438f13

commit_message:
Remove from BridgeDevice homemade execute in namespace

Currently BridgeDevice[1] defines homemade execute with namespace
support but could use IPWrapper. This change replaces homemade
implementation with IPWrapper use to respect DRY principle.

[1] neutron.agent.linux.bridge_lib

Change-Id: I12d4d40432e57ce8b6960276c41321c1efd98705

get_more_nodes's 3rd tier to use just ip instead of ip_ports
to make cluster's failure domain to be mapped to actual hardware.
See [1] in detail.

Tiers definition here is as:

To fix such a situation, this patch changes get_more_nodes to use
just IP at the 3rd tier.

1: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191970

commit_message:
Use just IP on get_more_nodes, too

According to Sam's change[1], for now, we should change
get_more_nodes's 3rd tier to use just ip instead of ip_ports
to make cluster's failure domain to be mapped to actual hardware.
See [1] in detail.

Tiers definition here is as:
1st: Region, 2nd: Zone, 3rd: Ip (previously Ip_ports), 4th: Device

In addition, if we keep current behavior and assign different
ports to each disk in the node, get_more_nodes would do device
level search twice w/o ip level search. (at 3rd and 4th tier)
That's unfortunately wasted and not to ensure ip-level failure domain.

To fix such a situation, this patch changes get_more_nodes to use
just IP at the 3rd tier.

1: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191970

Change-Id: I65d1b0ac904a074b235ed619d73cd0e33183b2c0

commit_message:
API Extensions: inherit from the ExtensionDescriptor

For consistency in the codebase, API extensions should inherit from the
abstract base class ExtensionDescriptor.

Change-Id: Id4829c265866e80c042c433bebcc01383e1e7417

commit_message:
Send mtu and vlan_transparent for network operations

We were previously removing these. But in the spirit of transparently
passing through all attributes and API calls from Neutron to ODL,
stop pruning these.

Change-Id: I741b7a4f53f6857499463a23b148dade14e41da2
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When

commit_message:
Unpin beaker-rspec

The latest version of beaker tries to manage sshd_config[1] in order to
pass through environment variables. JJB also tries to manage
sshd_config by adding Match blocks to securely allow root SSH[2]. When
beaker tries to append the PermitUserEnvironment line after the Match
blocks, SSH fails to open port 22 and beaker can't SSH in to the
node[3]. This patch unpins beaker-rspec and adds set_env: false to the
nodepool nodesets so that the set_env method is never called and does
not try to mess with the sshd_config.

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L528
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/jobs/puppet-module-jobs.yaml#n42
[3] http://logs.openstack.org/61/185161/1/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-beaker-rspec-dsvm-centos7/cd81608/console.html.gz#_2015-05-22_22_05_46_933
[4] https://github.com/puppetlabs/beaker/blob/master/lib/beaker/host_prebuilt_steps.rb#L502

Change-Id: I9752fd76266fcaf7ad27703799967d5468317781

commit_message:
Added documentation to Vagrantfile

A couple of comments during my latest CORS review indicated that
there is a misunderstanding on why the Vagrantfile in ironic exists.
In those comments, the assumption appeared to be that vagrant is used
to provision ironic, not just the development resources necessary to
work on ironic. This patch adds documentation to clarify that.

Change-Id: I7d71adaba402a62343d1e0399ee53410b76c973f

commit_message:
nova_powervm.virt.powervm.mgmt.rescan_scsi_bus

Add utility to rescan the SCSI bus, optionally with the 'remove' flag.

This is to be used when mapping instance disks to the management
partition, e.g. for the snapshot function.

Change-Id: Iea29cd2916607e1420ebb9654de3608c6534e6a5

commit_message:
Fix TypeError exception during cancel stack update

TypeError: call() takes exactly 3 arguments(5 given) is raised
during cancel stack update, this patch will fix the problem.

Change-Id: If85389150a15575d9e01466d950f8c07b8fa2717
Closes-Bug: #1448384
(cherry picked from commit 72403962033d15bfe910eae14f01a4461d1789e9)

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

commit_message:
Update devstack to handle Trove/Neutron setups

Default Trove configuration (for task manager and service) don't
reflect the settings required for Neutron. Trove requires a
configuration that can only be done after neutron is up. This
introduces a new function called just before starting trove services.

Change-Id: I197ec2d3975f7b551590cf1f6c7d2cb42d479e25
Closes-Bug: #1435612

commit_message:
Remove cloud-init details

If we have booted with cloud-init, then this status directory is
populated.  Remove it so when we boot snapshot images, they behave as
if on a fresh system.

Change-Id: Idc9ce01290b659e3239d30be847221447a8e5e84

commit_message:
Remove mount of ephemeral disk

hpcloud has started sending metadata to cloud-init to mount ephemeral
disks.  This ends up writing a fstab entry for /dev/vdb.

---
$ curl http://169.254.169.254/2009-04-04/meta-data/block-device-mapping/ephemeral0
/dev/vdb
---

It's unclear why this just started happening, but it did.

devstack-gate later attempts to repartition this into swap & disk
space and mount it elsewhere.  So remove this mount from fstab -- it
shouldn't come back because the next thing we do here is tell
cloud-init to not use the metadata source.

Change-Id: I3787d0f7e5139e891686ffbb2970e65d09f112b1

commit_message:
Set some more defaults for Linux Bridge

Set Linux Bridge to use VLANs for tenant networks, and designate eth0 as
the physical interface.

Co-Authored-By: Jens Rosenboom <j.rosenboom@x-ion.de>

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: If94671d03e36e737ed3557c1fc630540a506657e

from source until pkgs are available.

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

(4 comments)

The change set https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186908/ is similar but slightly orthogonal to this one.  That change set provided generic SCSI bus scanning capability - suitable for discovering newly-mapped devices *or* removing newly-unmapped devices - but no facility for detecting which newly-discovered device was the one we were looking for.

This change set provides discovery of newly-mapped devices - removal will be handled in a subsequent change set - and also finds a specific one we care about.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186908/ will likely be abandoned as soon as this change set's removal sister is in place."}, {'account_id': 14070, 'date': '2015-06-17 20:14:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-17 20:29:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add a mapped device to the management partition

New method nova_powervm.virt.powervm.mgmt.discover_vscsi_disk.

Based on a VSCSIMapping, scan the appropriate virtual SCSI host bus and
find the correct path of the newly-created device based on its UDID.

Change-Id: Id79b62fdd4f16f993b3563f20bc23d2d910f45a6

commit_message:
Remove duplicated debug logging around locking

Currently, iptables_manager.py does extra unnecessary logging about lock
acquisition and release. It uses lockutils.lock() which passes
do_log=True by default, which causes lockutils.lock() to do debug
logging about lock acquisition/release. IptablesManager itself also writes
debug log info about lock acquisition and release.

This change will eliminate unnecessary duplicate logging in order to
reduce log noise about locking. This change is also related to
https://github.com/harlowja/fasteners/commit/f88f2fea7fe250b7d26cdcbc84633ccbbc68eeee
which reduces the logging level in the underlying lock implementation
used by oslo.concurrency. That change along with this one will remove
the duplicate debug logging about locking in iptables_manager.py and also in
ipset_manager.py.

Change-Id: If6f4a7101f3783ad83645e28bbb5c577dd403d3b
Closes-Bug: 1464727

commit_message:
Enable loadbalancing of the Redis VIP, defaults to False

We have to set it to true as the default is false which means the
redis vip can't be reached. This was manifested as a problem with
ceilometer agent reaching the coordination url like [1].

Co-Authored-By: Giulio Fidente <gfidente@redhat.com>

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/attachment.cgi?id=1040023
Closes-Bug: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1232797
Change-Id: I1cd63308d0ac1d17542e1a2a909ee1a9680ed4b3

commit_message:
Fix MD5 headers regression

This regression was introduced when we switched to
swiftclient.service.SwiftService for uploading because of a
documentation bug. The option was listed as 'headers' but it should be
'header'.

Change-Id: Id590f624aa084af0747b93ae70b214600147ebb2

  - Removed write, list, and delete operations since they are not yet supported.
  - Added line for no additional properties other than "users" and "creator_only"
  - Added unit tests covering all of these and other conditions.
  - Updated unit tests to limit to "read" ACLs

commit_message:
Remove Future Parameters (write, list, delete) from ACL Validation Schema

Updated the validation schema for ACLs.
  - Removed write, list, and delete operations since they are not yet supported.
  - Added line for no additional properties other than "users" and "creator_only"
  - Added unit tests covering all of these and other conditions.
  - Updated unit tests to limit to "read" ACLs
  - Removed unit tests covering cases with more than one operation

Change-Id: Ie8a3abd22d02bb4a7bbedad373efa7435f3bdb3b
Closes-Bug: #1447872
(cherry picked from commit 1fa86f707e0b4b5923268fb34c87026d390e0eef)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

The #1 reason the AE Token spec was being considered was that it eliminates the need to have an unbounded data store of active tokens. In this case, you are instead of storing the complete token data, the HMAC - which is *still* unbounded.  

This issue means we will still run into the same problems with data storage. It isn't strictly an issue with the volume of data in the table but also an issue with the number of entries.

I would rather see the token provider cleanup succeed and this type of work occur out-of-tree as an optional provider unless it addresses the unbounded data-set issue. In short, I want to make the primary token provider(s) in keystone not rely on storing the token data [or a key-per-token issued, etc].


I am marking this with a -2 until we can spend some time discussing adding another token provider in-tree. This is not to kill the idea, but to force discussion on token providers, whether AE Token, HMAC, or some other version and placing them in-tree / having to maintain them in-tree."}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2015-02-08 15:29:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This adding the missing column in the policy table.

commit_message:
Revert "Switch defaults to stable/6.1"

Due to bug[1] in Gerrit, 6,1-only patchset has been applied  to master. We
obviously want to track master in master branch…

This reverts commit 218e92475d249ae3290f8d8343b14105b10412cd.

[1] https://code.google.com/p/gerrit/issues/detail?id=1107

Change-Id: Ic7ce1eea2baa279b7fee5f837922451dedfef7cc
Closes-Bug: 1466640

commit_message:
Setup for translation

To start translation, we need to initially import the
translation file - and place it at the proper place so that
the usual CI scripts can handle it.

The proper place is for all python projects
$PROJECT/locale/$PROJECT.pot - see setup.cfg.

Further imports will be done by the OpenStack Proposal bot.

Change-Id: I12910da652c462422915bd7090cde5598754ca14

commit_message:
Fix pep8 failures

This fixes the following failures when running "tox -e pep8":

./designatedashboard/dashboards/project/dns_domains/tables.py:55:15:
H201  no 'except:' at least use 'except Exception:'
        except:
              ^
./designatedashboard/dashboards/project/dns_domains/tables.py:177:5:
H238  old style class declaration, use new style (inherit from `object`)
    class Meta:
    ^
./designatedashboard/dashboards/project/dns_domains/tables.py:217:5:
H238  old style class declaration, use new style (inherit from `object`)
    class Meta:
    ^
./designatedashboard/tests/base.py:53:66: W292 no newline at end of file
        self.log_fixture = self.useFixture(fixtures.FakeLogger())

Change-Id: I33c4293edc16257ae8cebe7c76788075eae23a08

commit_message:
Change local disk tests to use flags()

The local disk tests were directly changing the CONF variables
rather than using self.flags().  This goes against the nova
hacking rules since it can effect downstream tests cases.

Change-Id: Ibc6e2d26d172d476680b9ffc06e02245180185ae

commit_message:
Add periodic propose-requirements-constraints jobs

Once a day, generate constraints files for all participating repos
and branches, and propose updates for them when necessary.

Change-Id: I9ae73a4b5547a9d601725ed5182d3a5ff69de651

Filter domain by name

Currently python-keystoneclient is broken (see [1]) so this patch changes
domain filter key to name.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-keystoneclient/+bug/1452298

commit_message:
Adding record-editor fip dropdown

This change adds an option drop down of floating ip addresses to use
for record creation / updates.  This simplifies the record setup process.

Change-Id: Ifa3d885ffb8683b88d6b0389ee89ef5121c484b8
Closes-bug: #1462022

commit_message:
Record creation / update screen simplification

This change moves the record create and update screen
so that users only need to provide the leftmost label of the
record they would like to use.

Change-Id: Id19220df2297f664251a9c0e0e19dfdc9740d16f
Closes-bug: #1461213

commit_message:
Correct dashboard domain details screen for juno

The domain detail screen contains code that requires newer horizon.
Juno should be supported, and this change enables that.

Change-Id: I1640f71bd5927928740aaea3ea61369c93574872
Closes-Bug: #1446281

Import only modules and update tox.ini

As stated in the OpenStack Hacking Guidelines, it is prefered

Also updated tox.ini to ignore opestack/common among others.

subject: Document needed pins for Puppet
messages:
[{'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-05-15 11:12:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-15 11:13:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/78/183478/1/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/3a3528c//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 33s'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-15 11:23:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

Documenting these seems like a good first step, but I'd probably add a "go look at what tripleo-ci is using and make sure these are the same" sentence, so folks know where the most current source of truth is for pinned versions.

I was actually thinking earlier, it'd be way better if we could maintain these pins in one place, either by having them set directly in a file inside tripleo-incubator (which CI then consumes), or by having e.g devtest pull the tripleo-ci repo and extract the pins CI is using.  

This would help us start moving away from every developer maintaining their own special environment (which invariably breaks every.single.time when you re-devtest it until you realize some pin has changed), e.g more towards a model where devtest could "just work" and figure out more of the needed config by itself.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-15 13:25:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build failed (check-tripleo pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing


- check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/78/183478/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha/500cd56/ : SUCCESS in 1h 09m 47s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/78/183478/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20-nonha/1ce938d/ : SUCCESS in 1h 36m 02s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20puppet-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/78/183478/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20puppet-nonha/555dd71/ : SUCCESS in 1h 40m 02s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/78/183478/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha/a7492ad/ : FAILURE in 1h 45m 15s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20puppet-ha http://logs.openstack.org/78/183478/1/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20puppet-ha/ca415b0/ : FAILURE in 1h 26m 55s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-05-21 18:38:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

A couple of thoughts here.

I don't think we want our default instructions linking to specific commits of puppet modules, or a specific DELOREAN_URL.

For the puppet-concat "pin" I would rather see us use a stable-puppet-dependencies element like this: I0267169e1c3b09d781e62cb4a2bd05143351dedd

The idea is that we pin only the dependencies (not the puppet/stackforge* modules themselves).

If we buy that approach perhaps this patch goes away and/or becomes a modification to our overcloud_puppet_disk_images.yaml to simply use that module for stability.

----

As for DELOREAN the approach I would like to see is slightly different. I would rather us actually have an upstream TripleO CI job targeted at Delorean package changes... We could have a job constantly running on the 'current' repo and if it passes we then 'tag' it into a 'tripleo-stable' repository which is know as good to pass the TripleO CI tests. There has already been some talk of doing this for other CI systems within the RDO community (these systems would create their own tags however). So there is some work required here... but I'd rather avoid hard coding the DELOREAN URL here long term and invest in a more self maintaining approach here.

So I'd rather see us do this (once we support it, instead):

  export DELOREAN_REPO_URL="http://trunk.rdoproject.org/f21/tripleo-stable/"'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-05-21 19:02:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

sure, all good points. my main intent here is to come away with a documented set of steps for how we can actually deploy with puppet, something we haven't had for several weeks. It would be nice to see that resolved while we finangle the finer points of how we want to handle this longer term."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-06-18 19:43:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Document needed pins for Puppet

We've been running with these in CI for a while. While it's not ideal to
have to document them here as well, there's no way for someone to try
anything with Puppet because we know they will fail when not using these
pins.

If this spot isn't ideal, I'm open to other ideas about where to commit
this info  but we need to doc this stuff somewhere so we don't have to
tell people who hit issues to "go look at what tripleo-ci is using".

Change-Id: Ic76c974e162f61e117a97376a9ca54b608b51f63

commit_message:
Update rabbitmq to v3.5.3-1

This change updates rabbitmq to the latest stable rabbitmq release
the new version is v3.5.3-1 and is being done to ensure that we are
maintaining a stable release with updated bug fixes and patches.

Closes-Bug: #1466589
Change-Id: I6d8a367a896194d3a1f8f64fc04e08a06078d1ec

commit_message:
Move get_inteface_by_ip from LinuxBridge class to ip_lib

get_interface_by_ip is moved fro LinuxBridgeManager to ip_lib
as a more generic get_device_by_ip.

System-faking unit tests have been switched in favor of functional
testing that also performs a negative tests.

This can be reused in the openvswitch-agent code to validate
local_ip reusing the LinuxBridge logic.

Change-Id: I9237871a6e24dd99556c71844624be510e20d289
Related-Bug: #1464178
Related-Bug: #1408603

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Ib8dce97aefcbe1157ee161d00082e97773e9e132

commit_message:
[EDP] Allow editing datasource objects

Currently there is no way to edit a datasource object. If a path needs
to be changed, for example, the datasource must be deleted and a new
one created. The most common use case is a situation where a user
creates a datasource, runs a job, and receives an error from the job
because the path does not exist. Although it is not strictly necessary,
editable datasource objects would be a convenience when a user needs to
correct a path or credentials.

blueprint edp-edit-data-sources

Change-Id: Idaef58f596b59a67f1fe953f9cd99a3a10932382

Record the paths that were used to retrieve job binaries.

Otherwise, we force the deletion of job execution records just to be able to edit a job binary.'}, {'account_id': 6116, 'date': '2015-05-06 07:03:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

There are two types of storage type for job binaries.

For data processing internal job binaries, they should not be changed if the job binaries already been executed, right ?'}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2015-05-06 20:18:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Well, there are JobBinary objects, which just store a URL.  And there are JobBinaryInternal objects which are mostly invisible to the end user and represent a blob in the Sahara database holding an executable.

A JobBinary just contains a URL, either a swift url or one of the form "internal-db://id" where "id" is the database id of the executable blob.

So, allowing a JobBinary URL to be replaced won't wipe out the original blob. It will still be there.

As I noted above, maybe if we want to allow editing of JobBinary objects we need to store the list of binary urls in the job executions as we (will) do for datasources.'}, {'account_id': 8411, 'date': '2015-05-06 22:49:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6116, 'date': '2015-05-07 06:20:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Trevor McKay	
 
The JobBinaryInternal object is managed directly in JobBinary tap in UI, where user can download and delete it.


If a JobBinary URL has changed, Because JobBinaryInternal objects are invisible to the end users, then user would not be able to download and delete JobBinaryInternal objects anymore, right ?'}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2015-05-07 13:08:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@li,

  yes, you are right, the UI blurs the line between JobBinary and JobBinaryInternal. Have to think through this a little more.'}, {'account_id': 8090, 'date': '2015-05-13 21:03:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sounds like a good summit discussion.'}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2015-05-15 19:18:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@li,chen,

 after taking a peek at the UI again, I agree.  Editing the URL itself for a job binary that points to a job binary internal doesn't make any sense -- the URL is constructed by Sahara and can't possibly be wrong.

I can see allowing name and description to be modified in that case, but not URL. I'll modify the spec to reflect that."}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2015-05-15 19:55:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2015-05-15 19:58:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-15 20:03:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
[EDP] Allow editing job binaries

Currently there is no way to edit a job binary. If a path needs
to be changed, for example, the job binary must be deleted and a new
one created. The most common use case is a situation where a user
creates a job binary, runs a job, and receives an error from the job
because the path does not exist. Although it is not strictly necessary,
editable job binary objects would be a convenience when a user needs to
correct a path or credentials.

Change-Id: Ic376796e32e0164ada86626438e79c5d2bbf59e9
blueprint: edp-edit-job-binaries

- http://10.15.25.125:8080/job/noop-check-communication/277/ : SUCCESS in 0s'}, {'account_id': 13768, 'date': '2015-06-17 11:52:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Let's continue holy war about static vs instance method started in [1].

There are reasons why it should be static and why it should be instance method.

Why instance:

- Using static methods in OOP context usually adds some complications or odd constructions (when you need to call super or call another class methods that can be redefined)

Why static:

- In this particular case reference to class/instance is not needed, because _rebuild_availability_ranges don't call super or any other class methods inside.

Deciding which reason is more important is purpose of this review.

I'd personally vote for static, because we don't hit any OOP limitaion in this particular case.
In case if static is preferred by other folks too, I'll just abandon this review.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190668/2/neutron/db/ipam_backend_mixin.py"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-17 12:39:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Convert rebuilding ranges to instance method

_rebuild_availability_ranges has to be redefined for non pluggable
backend, so making it instance method instead of static.

In case of converting _rebuild_availability_ranges to instance method,
_generate_ip should also be converted, because
_rebuild_availability_ranges is called from _generate_ip.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: Id8d8446f1014a066aa9390e560e453089ebf01bd

commit_message:
Convergence: Minor fixes

- adjust sync_point logic to account for deletes
      Done by having only a single stack sync point
      for both updates and deletes.
- Serialize/deserialize input_data for RPC
- Make GraphKey's the norm in convergence worker

Change-Id: I77b81097d2dcf01efa540237ed5ae14896ed1670

commit_message:
Add a non-voting py34 check job to Glance

Only add the check job to the master branch, ignore Kilo branches and
older since they will not get Python 3 support.

Change-Id: I95b3a1c3bee409bdb1f866515db0c6942620e359

VMware: remove dead function in vim_util

continue_to_get_objects() is moved to oslo.vmware as
continue_retrieval()

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I77fabb2ac16495379173b9d69f12ae060e699531

commit_message:
Enable flake8 checking of ironic/nova/*

The directory ironic/nova/* was being excluded from the flake8 check.

Make some minor whitespace and comment changes to
ironic/nova/compute/manager.py to make it pass the flake8 checks.

Change-Id: I5a76550db3b28a87964d1505441246cdb0354ee7

in the code.

In the ring builder, we place partitions with maximum possible
dispersion across tiers, where a "tier" is region, then zone, then
IP/port,then device. Now, instead of IP/port, just use IP. The port
wasn't really getting us anything; two different object servers on two
different ports on one machine aren't separate failure
domains. However, if someone has only a few machines and is using one
object server on its own port per disk, then the ring builder would
end up with every disk in its own IP/port tier, resulting in bad (with
respect to durability) partition placement.

For example: assume 1 region, 1 zone, 4 machines, 48 total disks (12
per machine), and one object server (and hence one port) per
disk. With the old behavior, partition replicas will all go in the one
region, then the one zone, then pick one of 48 IP/port pairs, then
pick the one disk therein. This gives the same result as randomly
picking 3 disks (without replacement) to store data on; it completely
ignores machine boundaries.

With the new behavior, the replica placer will pick the one region,
then the one zone, then one of 4 IPs, then one of 12 disks
therein. This gives the optimal placement with respect to durability.

Change-Id: Ibbd740c51296b7e360845b5309d276d7383a3742

commit_message:
Use just IP, not port, when determining partition placement

In the ring builder, we place partitions with maximum possible
dispersion across tiers, where a "tier" is region, then zone, then
IP/port,then device. Now, instead of IP/port, just use IP. The port
wasn't really getting us anything; two different object servers on two
different ports on one machine aren't separate failure
domains. However, if someone has only a few machines and is using one
object server on its own port per disk, then the ring builder would
end up with every disk in its own IP/port tier, resulting in bad (with
respect to durability) partition placement.

For example: assume 1 region, 1 zone, 4 machines, 48 total disks (12
per machine), and one object server (and hence one port) per
disk. With the old behavior, partition replicas will all go in the one
region, then the one zone, then pick one of 48 IP/port pairs, then
pick the one disk therein. This gives the same result as randomly
picking 3 disks (without replacement) to store data on; it completely
ignores machine boundaries.

With the new behavior, the replica placer will pick the one region,
then the one zone, then one of 4 IPs, then one of 12 disks
therein. This gives the optimal placement with respect to durability.

The same applies to Ring.get_more_nodes().

Co-Authored-By: Kota Tsuyuzaki <tsuyuzaki.kota@lab.ntt.co.jp>

Change-Id: Ibbd740c51296b7e360845b5309d276d7383a3742

commit_message:
Disallow backing files when uploading volumes to image

Volumes with a header referencing a backing file can leak
file data into the destination image when uploading a
volume to an image.

Halt the upload process if the volume data references a
backing file to prevent this.

Closes-Bug: #1415087
Change-Id: Iab9718794e7f7e8444015712cfa08c46848ebf78
(cherry picked from commit b1143ee45323e63b965a3710f9063e65b252c978)

cannot be added by the Hyper-V Security Groups Driver, as it cannot add
rules with the protocol 'icmpv6'.

Creates stateless ICMPv6 security group rules properly.

Closes-Bug: #1466547
(cherry picked from commit 1ea0f15e6a3b050e1301274496494d732d18f0d9)
"}]
commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes Security Group Driver ICMPv6 rules

Security Group rules created with ethertype 'IPv6' and protocol 'icmp'
cannot be added by the Hyper-V Security Groups Driver, as it cannot add
rules with the protocol 'icmpv6'.

Creates stateless ICMPv6 security group rules properly.

Change-Id: Id49294965c7adb6d4fbc6c799e4ae7f30070bb71
Closes-Bug: #1466547
(cherry picked from commit 1ea0f15e6a3b050e1301274496494d732d18f0d9)

I like where this is going, but my biggest concern is exposing vendor-specific stuff at the top level like this. It's going to get out of hand when we have multiple implementations and we've taken a more interface/implementation sort of division for other such things.

For example, take a look at how the network configuration is done. It uses a combination of the resource registry (to specify a particular implementation of a resource type) and parameter_defaults (to bypass the normal passing of parameters and not require all of those parameters to be defined at the top level).

I think that's what we want here. Keep the "interface" -- which is to say, the common parameters -- as thin as possible. Use the resource_registry to enable a specific backend (removing the enable_netapp_backend flag entirely), and then parameter_defaults to be able to pass in netapp specific information.

Ping me in chat if you have more questions. If you take a look at the commits in the past day or two, you'll see the network changes I referred to.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 19:39:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Enable NetApp Backends in Cinder

Enables support for configuring Cinder with a NetApp backend.
This change adds all relevant parameters for:
 - Clustered Data ONTAP (NFS, iSCSI, FC)
 - Data ONTAP 7-Mode (NFS, iSCSI, FC)
 - E-Series (iSCSI)

Change-Id: I5fea93aee61357ed22973a1bb7eef45799aa823c

commit_message:
Ensure that service values are strings

Sometimes ints can sneak in in api version values. We never want that.

Change-Id: I730be13d3328bdee1652186021ee1579f8ef4b57

commit_message:
Fix incompatiblity issue in VNX manila driver

When running Manila with VNX File OE 8.1.6 or later,
if user creates a NFS share in Manila, driver will
report nas command error when setting nfs permission.

This fix will use updated nas command to resolve it.

Change-Id: I0550cdf01278fa4e9aeed7891152fed6dcc0eefc
Closes-Bug: #1465543
(cherry picked from commit 081f9226e46ba801ba7be8024aebb967aba7f2e9)

commit_message:
Run oslo.db unit tests with MySQL-Python too

While PyMySQL is now a default for all OpenStack projects, we still
want to make sure oslo.db works correctly with MySQL-Python, as there
might people who want to use it that way.

Depends-On: I12b32dc097a121bd43991bc38dd4d289b65e86c1

commit_message:
Add support for WEBROOT in local_settings

Starting in Kilo, a new WEBROOT setting has been added in file
local_settings (see
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/horizon/topics/settings.html).
This requires changes in the Apache vhost configuration, too.

Change-Id: Ibbeec600502964b51c0c725c35d2afd6fd7bd9e9

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes Security Group Driver ICMPv6 rules

Security Group rules created with ethertype 'IPv6' and protocol 'icmp'
cannot be added by the Hyper-V Security Groups Driver, as it cannot add
rules with the protocol 'icmpv6'.

Creates stateless ICMPv6 security group rules properly.

Change-Id: Id49294965c7adb6d4fbc6c799e4ae7f30070bb71
Closes-Bug: #1466547

commit_message:
Configurable lxc cache and rootfs path

The rootfs of the containers use large disk space and is defaulted to
/var/lib/lxc. It's desirable to configure an alternative rootfs directory on a
partition with large enough free space to hold the rootfs.

The rootfs of a container is hard-linked to the lxc cache when created by lxc
templates. Therefore both have to reside on the same partition and the lxc
cache shall be configurable as well as the rootfs directory.

The lxc-ubuntu template is patched by lxc-host role to use the configured lxc
cache folder. This patch should be removed once the updated upstream lxc with
support of configuring the cache path goes mainstream.

To confgiure these parameters, set the following variables in global_overrides
of openstack_user_config.yml:
    - lxc_container_directory, defaults to /var/lib/lxc
    - lxc_container_cache_path, defaults to /var/cache/lxc

Closes-Bug: #1463905
Change-Id: I9ccf0c45e0a1875644750e0d70ce613265040176
(cherry picked from commit de2dc69641d41f1a1e42dec4374f708634af55a9)

commit_message:
[Manila] Add scenario for creation and deletion of Manila shares

List of changes:
- Added support of 'create' and 'delete' operations for shares.
- Added benchmark for creating and deleting shares without usage
of share networks.

> Note: you start with an empty repo, you will need to have the first submission setup all the gating infrastructure.

Good point, I might reduce the gates to just the basics until everything is lined up!

Also - We intend to re-use olso's tooling to extract history etc from the current contrib/designate-dashboard folder in the Designate git repo - so, I expect we'll need one of the infra team / a Project Bootstrapper's member to do an initial push for us.

> I'll setup transifex for this project now so that the translations should work - but expect that this needs a a few iterations to get fully working and maybe some changes to the repo. Your initial commit should setup the translations properly.

Thanks - I'll make sure we cover this.

> I'm not seeing a change to gerritbot/channels.yaml. Do you want the designate channel get notified about changes?

Good catch, I have another revision to do on this review anyway after speaking to David Lyle a few minutes ago re giving horizon-core +2."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-08 16:22:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Kiall, if you want to do an initial import, import the file. This is documented at http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/creators.html#add-the-repository-to-the-master-repositories-list - using the upstream tag. So, create a repository using git filter and set it up *now* and then it gets automatically import.

Infra will not push any history for you.'}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2015-06-08 16:28:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

the test code (at least the tox stuff) does not work 100% right now (for the designate-dashboard), I believe.  I think for now we might want to just run with pep8 checks and then add the unit tests later on.

This is b/c getting django unit tests running is a bear, especially in how to pull in horizon to also work like a test foundation piece.   I have talked with Dave Lyle and I think he is unsure of the correct thing to do right now as well.'}, {'account_id': 8099, 'date': '2015-06-17 13:32:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-17 13:53:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add openstack/designate-dashboard to the DNS Services project

This repository will be used for the Designate Horizon dashboard which
currently lives in designate's contrib/designate-dashboard folder. Having
it's own repo will make enabling gates, tarball releases, etc significantly
easier.

Change-Id: Iab108e88621035f04b9e21bf57ba4e9dd4c6e3f1

commit_message:
Fix Manila jobs for running on stable/juno branch

Manila uses 'plugin' approach in Devstack since Kilo. So, when Manila Tempest
jobs are running against 'stable/juno' branch of Manila it is just not
installed and all Tempest tests are skipped because of that. So, make jobs
distinguish two different approaches for setup of Manila using Devstack.

Change-Id: Ifb020fe8693fd4f014e944aad0c96a1e67843e4e

commit_message:
Add path_args to create and update proxy methods

Nothing is using this as of this change, but I need them in object_store
to properly create and update objects and their metadata. There's no
test update since nothing is making use of it.

Change-Id: Ic20ce1f7f7daae50565331de53945fc033a12106

commit_message:
Update the merge process for Liberty

We need to do a better job of getting visibility from the Cross
Project Liaisons. This process engages the CPLs on various
channels to ensure maximum visibility before merging a guideline.

Change-Id: I58adab3d84aacde8a6835fe696273c39ea5e53a5

commit_message:
Targets tests: Clean up long lines

Clean up long lines in unit tests, mostly by
using a variable for volume UUID and shortening
unnecessarily long CHAP credentials.

This is not intended to be complete, just
a good start that greatly reduces #noqa and
improves readability.

Change-Id: Iddc26a5722731d76e6d9e4b0ff493ed806bf148d

The patch increase minimal testtools version from 0.9.36 to
minimal version where testtools.TestCase is inherited from
unittest2.TestCase (instead of unittest.TestCase).
It allows to rely on single implementation of TestCase(unittest2
only) and use some features of unittest2(for example,
some projects like Sahara, Heat use self.assertRegex in test cases
but this method is supported in unittest2 only. So we need to

Change-Id: I24d13c7701b7314e3599c94701af4b38d2dabefb
'}]
commit_message:
Increase testtools version to support unittest2

The patch increase minimal testtools version from 0.9.36 to
minimal version where testtools.TestCase is inherited from
unittest2.TestCase (instead of unittest.TestCase).
It allows to rely on single implementation of TestCase(unittest2
only) and use some features of unittest2(for example,
some projects like Sahara, Heat use self.assertRegex in test cases
but this method is supported in unittest2 only. So we need to
increase the minimal version of testtools to support this method).

Change-Id: I24d13c7701b7314e3599c94701af4b38d2dabefb

commit_message:
Fix python ironicclient default version

Change from '1.0' => '1' client version to enable import of the client.

Change-Id: Ic3ead1422e352cc73d50e20e5846c55a92de601f

commit_message:
Refactor rpc_loop() in ovs neutron agent

This patch segregates the port_info recieved by
scan_ports and scan_ancillary_ports.

This refactoring is basically required for this patch set:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/165023/

Co-Authored-By: Romil Gupta <romilg@hp.com>

Change-Id: I9b43c230cda9d2659ad0e806bebe8a3dc12826ec

Refactoring for configurarion/jobs and matching for the arguments in freezerc from UI

Configuration files are now named Job files
Job file creation now matchs the arguments from freezerc
Overview endpoint

*Do not merge*

commit_message:
Remove contextlib.nested from tests

With the deprecation of this method in Python2.7, the neutron hacking
check has been modified to check for this (N324). Since this check has
been upstreamed (I171fbdb89892a3d4548bf2ca52f4a7dd9ef8dccb), and the
neutron-vpnaas repo uses the same hacking check, the VPN test cases
are now failing.

This commit does the same changes as was done in neutron to remove use
of this method.

Change-Id: Ie490e89c1a65e126ad0a57d062076e472762837e
Partial-Bug: 1428424

commit_message:
Support for AMT

Addition of dependencies to support AMT nodes, as well as enabling
the driver in the ironic.conf file that is written out to disk.

Change-Id: Ice505eb333c9dbf33262fd7061d7fcf808ea77b5
Co-Authored-By: Devananda van der Veen <devananda.vdv@@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Julia Kreger <juliaashleykreger@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Run worldump if tempest fails

If things go wrong during devstack's setup we run worlddump. Lets run
the same thing if something in tempest goes wrong, so we can collect
more data.

This will allow us to do things like trigger guru meditation reports in
nova-compute to see what it is doing (if it hangs etc.)

Change-Id: I035fe8e3333034e44b403ed0f986220ab5b0e57a

commit_message:
Compute: use instance object for _deleted_old_enough method

The method _get_instances_on_driver returns instance objects so
we can use the dot notation and drop the validation that the
instance is an object.

Change-Id: Ibde61483956485d57336438b517135617b235887

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/38/186638/1/check/noop/4111393/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 4625, 'date': '2015-05-29 13:49:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I wonder if we should specify the TYPE of attribute values as a conventional practice.

for example if 'bug_link' is always a list that may make it easier to parse than if it's either a string or a list of strings.

I'd like this but not so much I'd -1 over it, but I would like to see the idea discussed before we push our first tags."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:30:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Tom, please discuss with the documentation team. This really needs collaboration. We might not add an Install Guide for all projects but will concentrate on some smaller subset.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:32:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

That is indeed what this tag is for - is there an install guide or not :)

If there's no install guide for a project (eg because of docs team choice not to support), that's something an op should know when making a choice about whether to use it or not.

Or am I missing something?"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:36:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So, is this only about the Documentation Deliverable Install Guide? Then let's have the Doc team co-own this."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:40:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Just join the ops tags team, it'll make things much simpler :) This is a user-perspective tag, under the governance of the user committee."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:48:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:50:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Tom, sync the projects with governance/reference/projects.yaml - there are more than the m* like Congress.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-01 08:56:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the tip Andreas.

Thinking about it - maybe it's better to have an implicit "not available" for this tag, rather than trying to list every project.'}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2015-06-01 09:28:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-01 09:32:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for your continued review Maish!'}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2015-06-01 09:48:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-06-01 13:05:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

Comments inline, the main one being that the current common install guide should have an additional counterpart once we figure out how to aggregate install guides across repos and have the teams maintain their own install guides... see ironic example inline.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-01 14:00:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

Thanks for the comments Anne, I've given very quick replies inline that I hope should help clarify :)"}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-06-01 22:18:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Ok, that helps. I'd suggest starting with one month after release for applying/removing this tag."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-02 01:42:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So, starting a month after release would artificially limit the information available to operators: we actually want them to know that the install guide isn't available for that month.

Is there a reason we wouldn't provide that information, given that ops tags are all about capturing community-inherit knowledge and presenting it in an easily consumable form?

Here's how I see it working:


<-- potential for tag update here

1) OpenStack is released

<-- potential for tag update here

2) Docs are released

<-- potential for tag update here

3) Mass bug reports come in and docs are fixed.

<-- potential for tag update here"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:22:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Looks good in general, but I think it would be simpler (and easier to navigate) if tags were just binary, rather than have multiple attributes.

Here I'm thinking of the websites that will be built soon to expose that information to the public. For TC tags we've restricted ourselves to purely binary tags (it's there or it's not) so that the information is simple to present, and does not substitute to proper documentation.

So I see 3 ways out of this maze:

1/ Turn ops tags into purely binary beings
This is pretty simple for this tag, just drop the idea of storing comments in it.

2/ Publish a companion doc to expand on the tag
The tag is still binary, but has wiki/documentation associated to it to provide extra information. For this tag, that would mean moving comments to an associated document that further explains the status.

3/ Really provide ops metrics but then don't call them tags
Reduce confusion by not using the same word for different things.

I tend to prefer 1 or 2 because that allows us to still publish them on the project tag navigation website."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-03 14:34:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks ttx!

So, #1 just doesn't work at all with the whole underlying idea of providing information to ops as our goal.

#2 I think complicates both the process of updating the tag and also using the information for display. Based on your comments, I don't think we have a common view on how this information should be displayed.

I guess this leaves #3, but I don't understand what "metrics" are in this context :)'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-06-11 02:44:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 02:45:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

Hi all,

Update to address in-line comments. Paticularly

1) reword the tag description to remove reference to a specific document, to give the doc team (and us) flexibility

2) Fix Maish's comment regarding all or nothing for the application

3) Change deprecation section to "tag updates and timing" to explain how this tag will be updated, based on discussion with Ann

4) Fix Json syntax errors


Your feedback on these in particular is welcome!'}, {'account_id': 4625, 'date': '2015-06-18 15:24:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4625, 'date': '2015-06-18 15:45:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-18 15:45:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Add ops:docs:install-guide tag

As discussed at the summit, a first simple tag to achieve would
be ops:docs:install-guide, which provides information to operators regarding
the existence and quality of install documentation for the project.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/YVR-ops-tags

Change-Id: I1a28f58cad89688bfe85b5a76e63aa89aeb5db89

[{'created': '2015-06-17 10:17:13.000000000', 'message': 'Move explicit URLs in ironic-install to defaults

To facilitate offline installs, any explicit URLs should be
moved to a location where they can be easily overridden with
a local equivalent.

That way, a default install will use the canonical location, but
a user can easily override this behavior in inventory.

(Such gymnastics are not necessary for apt/yum/pip, because those
can be configured to point to local/alternate repositories independently).

** WIP - Needs documentation **

Change-Id: I9dada2fe769e30abc06dac092b9f47b99969a954
Closes-Bug: #1464787

commit_message:
Move explicit URLs in ironic-install to defaults

To facilitate offline installs, any explicit URLs should be
moved to a location where they can be easily overridden with
a local equivalent.

That way, a default install will use the canonical location, but
a user can easily override this behavior in inventory.

(Such gymnastics are not necessary for apt/yum/pip, because those
can be configured to point to local/alternate repositories independently).

** WIP - Needs *better* documentation **

Change-Id: I9dada2fe769e30abc06dac092b9f47b99969a954
Closes-Bug: #1464787

commit_message:
Update version for Liberty

Update the version for Liberty, switching from date-based versioning
to pre-versioning using SemVer. See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/065211.html
and
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067082.html
for details.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

commit_message:
Remove rally.deploy.__main__ hacks

These hacks make the code hard to read and create a mess of
imports, which doesn't allow us to optimize them
and reduce rally start up time.

Change-Id: I4fce652bb6c5fbdcc6e7416164baf7f2254f9c16

commit_message:
Add a non-voting py34 check job to Cinder

Only add the check job to the master branch, ignore Kilo branches and
older since they will not get Python 3 support.

Blueprint cinder-python3

commit_message:
Create Magnum UI repo

The Magnum community has evaluated inclusion of this project and decided on a
governance approach for managing this project in Magnum.

Reference:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/066701.html

The Technical Committee is evaluating the addition of magnum-ui to the openstack
git namespace in a Magnum governance change.

Reference: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192804/

Change-Id: Ice2e14bf999f79ca0c0718948db616456faab907

commit_message:
Removes is_available() from manila client plugin

python-manilaclient is already added in the requirements.txt and
manilaclient will be always available. so it is not required to
check the existance of manilaclient module and is removed in this
patch.

Change-Id: If2b85599fd4df49c9aa80af10079adb51afe4dd1

Could someone clarify what the "mature" means? Does it mean we need to get all the codes completed? Is there a link to the guideline or criteria so that we know the gap and can address it accordingly? Here is the current status of this project: the spec has been reviewed by the community since it was uploaded in April and eight updated versions have been uploaded which incorporated the comments/input. Two audio meetings and three IRC meetings have been conducted and we have reached consensus on the architecture and its relationship to Neutron as well as module pieces that need to be developed for supporting this feature. In last IRC meeting, people from different companies as well as individual contributors have volunteered to sign up for development of each piece.  We are now waiting for this repository to be ready to start develop and check in codes. We would appreciate guidance of how to pull the repository properly so that we do no need to do rebase, and also appreciate clear criteria about how we can get this feature accepted into OpenStack smoothly (Thanks for the guidance from the openstack-infra which is very helpful for us to move forward with this feature development) since this feature is needed by many customers. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-06-17 18:14:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the brief status update. We all realize that experimentation is done with the user in mind: stating that this is needed by customers is almost like stating the obvious :) Let me go through your points one by one and hopefully provide you with some answers:

> Could someone clarify what the "mature" means?

There is no exact definition here, as maturity may be perceived differently from one person to another. In my opinion, a mature project is a project that has demonstrated value, it's collaborated on by multiple parties, and it goes beyond the bootstrapping phase. 

> Does it mean we need to get all the codes completed? Is there a link to the guideline or criteria so that we know the gap and can address it accordingly? 

Not at all, in my opinion; one might argue that 'code complete' is something that happens at every end of cycle, but we'll never be done so long as there is user feedback and we'll keep on working on refining/improving the functionality that needs to be delivered. In the process, we need to make sure we respect the OpenStack Open principles [1], and we need to make sure that the project integrates well with Neutron from various angles. This will take time, and possibly many release cycles.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Open'}]

commit_message:
Rename ServiceNetMap: NeutronLocalIp

This patch renames the NeutronLocalIp option to be called
NeutronTenantNetwork. This is more consistent with
all of the other ServiceNetMap settings which end in
'Network' and initial end user feedback found the
old name a bit cryptic as well.

This is the network for neutron tenant traffic so lets
just name it that.

Change-Id: Id49afe75c372887453413c092190a5775aa3e1ee

commit_message:
Add client_socket_timeout parameter

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet
socket timeout behaviour. Allows closing idle client
connections after a period of time.

Leaving the sockets open may allow malefactors to attack the
system by creating many simultaneous connections, which leads
to significant cpu consumption by glance-api servers.

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I129edb4cf6372165ce8ba3759bb40beadba9cdda

commit_message:
fuel_upgrade: setup update/security repos

In order to deliver bugfixes and improvements to customers we have to
setup our online repos in case of successful upgrade. These repos
have to be marked with "skip_if_available" flag so yum won't fall
if there's no connectivity to them (e.g. no Internet access).

Closes-Bug: #1466418

Change-Id: I6626ff5e92c53c487f69491c09c3e0bcf022d5d4
Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

commit_message:
Bump oslo.utils to >= 1.6.0

This oslo.utils release has some new utility code that can
make it possible to remove code from at least the tooz and
taskflow projects/libraries.

Mainly these new additions can allow those projects to remove
some similar code:

- exception_to_unicode() function
- raise_with_cause() function

Change-Id: Id97b5dd5a0fb30222ef5ca264882f6e0fdaf1424

commit_message:
Return True/False for delete methods

This changes many (not all) of our delete methods to have consistent
return values: True if the resource was deleted, False if it was not
found for deletion.

The methods being changed here either returned nothing at all, or
they raised an exception on resource not found. The ones that raised
an exception no longer raise this exception, and instead return False.

We also make sure that a debug log message is output for a delete
request that could not find the resource.

Change-Id: I0ee4654dc6f68b475179d36002fe9db713e26290
